{"title_page": "Jai Shri Ram", "text_new": "{{Italics}} \n{{short description|Phrase meaning \"Hail Lord Rama\", often chanted in Hinduism}}\n[[File:Ram in Ayodhya.jpg|thumb|207x207px|A depiction of Ram in Ayodhya.]]\n'''''Jai Shri Ram''''' is a Hindi expression, translating to \"Glory to Lord [[Rama]]\" or \"Victory to Lord Rama\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=2019-07-10 |work=BBC News |access-date=2020-02-04 |language=en-GB}}</ref> The proclamation has been used as an informal greeting<ref>{{Cite book |last=Menon |first=Kalyani Devaki |url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/454038 |title=Everyday Nationalism: Women of the Hindu Right in India |date=2011-07-06 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=978-0-8122-0279-3 |page=190 |language=en |chapter=Notes |doi=10.9783/9780812202793 |jstor=j.ctt3fj1wh |chapter-url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/books/9780812202793/9780812202793.183/9780812202793.183.xml}}</ref> or as a symbol of adhering to Hindu [[faith]]<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Agrawal |first=Purushottam |date=1994 |title='Kan Kan Mein Vyape Hein Ram': The Slogan as a Metaphor of Cultural Interrogation |journal=Oxford Literary Review |volume=16 |issue=1/2 |pages=245\u2013264 |doi=10.3366/olr.1994.010 |issn=0305-1498 |jstor=44244508}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ghosh |first=Shohini |date=2000 |title=Hum Aapke Hain Koun...!: Pluralizing Pleasures of Viewership |journal=Social Scientist |volume=28 |issue=3/4 |pages=83\u201390 |doi=10.2307/3518192 |issn=0970-0293 |jstor=3518192}}</ref> or for projection of varied faith-centered emotions, by Hindus in recent past.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ramachandran |first=Tanisha |date=2014-03-01 |title=A call to multiple arms! protesting the commoditization of hindu imagery in western society |journal=Material Religion |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=54\u201375 |doi=10.2752/175183414X13909887177547 |issn=1743-2200}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |date=2019-08-20 |title=Modi's party will grow stronger in West Bengal |journal=Emerald Expert Briefings |language=en |doi=10.1108/OXAN-DB245910 |issn=2633-304X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dasgupta |first=Amlan |date=2006 |editor-last=Bakhle |editor-first=Janaki |title=Rhythm and Rivalry |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=41 |issue=36 |pages=3861\u20133863 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4418675}}</ref> \nThe expression was used by the [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) which embraced the slogan in the late 20th century, as a tool of increasing the visibility of Hinduism in public spaces and went on to use it as a war-cry, for perpetration of communal atrocities against people of other faiths.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Jaffrelot |first=Christophe |author-link=Christophe Jaffrelot |date=July 2003 |title=Communal Riots in Gujarat: The State at Risk? |url=http://archiv.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/volltextserver/4127/1/hpsacp17.pdf |journal=Heidelberg Papers in South Asian and Comparative Politics |issue=17 |page=3 |doi=10.11588/heidok.00004127 |issn=1617-5069}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Engineer |first=Asghar Ali |date=1993 |title=Bastion of Communal Amity Crumbles |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=7 |pages=262\u2013264 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399390}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Breman |first=Jan |date=1993 |title=Anti-Muslim Pogrom in Surat |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=16 |pages=737\u2013741 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399608}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nIn the  late 1980's, the slogan was popularised by [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s television series ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'', where it was used by [[Hanuman]] and the monkey army as a war cry when they fought the demon army of [[Ravan]] in order to free [[Sita]].<ref name=\"India Today\" /> The [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] and its [[Sangh Parivar]] allies, including the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], used it in their Ayodhya [[Ayodhya dispute|Ram Janmabhoomi movement]].<ref name=\"India Today\">{{Cite news |author=Prabash K. Dutta |title=Jai Shri Ram: A slogan that changed political contours of India |newspaper=India Today |date=13 July 2019 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/jai-shri-ram-a-slogan-that-changed-political-contours-of-india-1568051-2019-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vishva Hindu Parishad]]\n[[Category:Sangh Parivar]]\n[[Category:Ayodhya dispute]]\n[[Category:Violence against Muslims]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italics}} \n{{short description|Phrase meaning \"Hail Lord Rama\", often chanted in Hinduism}}\n[[File:Ram in Ayodhya.jpg|thumb|207x207px|A depiction of Ram in Ayodhya.]]\n'''''Jai Shri Ram''''' is a Hindi expression, translating to \"Glory to Lord [[Rama]]\" or \"Victory to Lord Rama\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=2019-07-10 |work=BBC News |access-date=2020-02-04 |language=en-GB}}</ref> The proclamation has been used as an informal greeting<ref>{{Cite book |last=Menon |first=Kalyani Devaki |url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/454038 |title=Everyday Nationalism: Women of the Hindu Right in India |date=2011-07-06 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=978-0-8122-0279-3 |page=190 |language=en |chapter=Notes |doi=10.9783/9780812202793 |jstor=j.ctt3fj1wh |chapter-url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/books/9780812202793/9780812202793.183/9780812202793.183.xml}}</ref> or as a symbol of adhering to Hindu [[faith]]<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Agrawal |first=Purushottam |date=1994 |title='Kan Kan Mein Vyape Hein Ram': The Slogan as a Metaphor of Cultural Interrogation |journal=Oxford Literary Review |volume=16 |issue=1/2 |pages=245\u2013264 |doi=10.3366/olr.1994.010 |issn=0305-1498 |jstor=44244508}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ghosh |first=Shohini |date=2000 |title=Hum Aapke Hain Koun...!: Pluralizing Pleasures of Viewership |journal=Social Scientist |volume=28 |issue=3/4 |pages=83\u201390 |doi=10.2307/3518192 |issn=0970-0293 |jstor=3518192}}</ref> or for projection of varied faith-centered emotions, by Hindus in recent past.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ramachandran |first=Tanisha |date=2014-03-01 |title=A call to multiple arms! protesting the commoditization of hindu imagery in western society |journal=Material Religion |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=54\u201375 |doi=10.2752/175183414X13909887177547 |issn=1743-2200}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |date=2019-08-20 |title=Modi's party will grow stronger in West Bengal |journal=Emerald Expert Briefings |language=en |doi=10.1108/OXAN-DB245910 |issn=2633-304X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dasgupta |first=Amlan |date=2006 |editor-last=Bakhle |editor-first=Janaki |title=Rhythm and Rivalry |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=41 |issue=36 |pages=3861\u20133863 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4418675}}</ref> \nThe expression was used by the [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) which embraced the slogan in the late 20th century, as a tool of increasing the visibility of Hinduism in public spaces and went on to use it as a war-cry, for perpetration of communal atrocities against people of other faiths.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Jaffrelot |first=Christophe |author-link=Christophe Jaffrelot |date=July 2003 |title=Communal Riots in Gujarat: The State at Risk? |url=http://archiv.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/volltextserver/4127/1/hpsacp17.pdf |journal=Heidelberg Papers in South Asian and Comparative Politics |issue=17 |page=3 |doi=10.11588/heidok.00004127 |issn=1617-5069}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Engineer |first=Asghar Ali |date=1993 |title=Bastion of Communal Amity Crumbles |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=7 |pages=262\u2013264 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399390}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Breman |first=Jan |date=1993 |title=Anti-Muslim Pogrom in Surat |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=16 |pages=737\u2013741 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399608}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nIn the  late 1980's, the slogan was popularised by [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s television series ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'', where it was used by [[Hanuman]] and the monkey army as a war cry when they fought the demon army of [[Ravan]] in order to free [[Sita]].<ref name=\"India Today\" /> The [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] and its [[Sangh Parivar]] allies, including the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], used it in their Ayodhya [[Ayodhya dispute|Ram Janmabhoomi movement]].<ref name=\"India Today\">{{Cite news |author=Prabash K. Dutta |title=Jai Shri Ram: A slogan that changed political contours of India |newspaper=India Today |date=13 July 2019 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/jai-shri-ram-a-slogan-that-changed-political-contours-of-india-1568051-2019-07-13}}</ref>\n\n== Usage in violent incidents ==\nIn 1992, during riots and [[Demolition of Babri Masjid]], the same slogans were raised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/19921231-babri-masjid-demolition-when-men-in-saffron-bandanas-struck-screaming-the-name-of-ram-767472-2013-05-21|title=Babri Masjid demolition: When men in saffron bandanas struck screaming the name of Ram|first1=Ravi Shankar|last1=May 21|first2=2013 ISSUE DATE:|last2=December 31|first3=1992UPDATED:|last3=July 25|first4=2013 13:22|last4=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=D'Costa |first1=Jasmine |title=Matter of Geography |date=2017 |publisher=Mosaic Press |isbn=978-1-77161-247-0 |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=TLRJDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT41&dq=Jai%20Shri%20Ram&pg=PT41#v=onepage&q=Jai%20Shri%20Ram&f=false |accessdate=11 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, before his [[Tabrez Ansari lynching|lynching, Tabrez Ansari]] was forced by the mob to chant religious slogans \"Jai Shree Ram\" and \"Jai Hanuman\".<ref name=\"BBC chant\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053|title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry|date=July 10, 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2020, in an [[Gargi College molestations|incident of mass molestation]] and sexual harassment at [[Gargi College]], the [[Communist Party of India|CPI's]] women association alleged that the perpetrators were chanting the slogan of \"Jay Shree Ram\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/they-shouted-jai-shri-slogans-cpis-womens-association-on-thugs-involved-in-gargi-college-mass-molestation-case|title='They shouted Jai Shri Slogans': CPI's women's association on thugs involved in Gargi College 'mass molestation' case|website=Free Press Journal}}</ref>\n\nThe chant was heard again later the same month as Hindutva-inspired rioters torched Muslim properties and houses during the [[North East Delhi riots]].<ref name=\"Delhi Riots\">{{cite news |title=Delhi Riots: Mosque Set on Fire in Ashok Nagar, Hanuman Flag Placed on Minaret |url=https://thewire.in/communalism/delhi-violence-mosque-set-on-fire-in-ashok-vihar-hanuman-flag-placed-on-top |accessdate=26 February 2020 |work=The Wire |date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ground Report: In Riot City, Hindutva Mobs Rage With Impunity as Police Watch in Silence|url=https://thewire.in/communalism/delhi-riots-jai-shri-ram-hindutva-bjp|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=26 February 2020|website=The Wire}}</ref> At least 20 people were killed in over three days of riots. Wounded residents fleeing the area described being beaten by mobs chanting the slogan, and being stopped multiple times by Hindus demanding they pull down their pants to show whether or not they were circumcised. <ref>{{cite news|title=Communal Violence Over India's Citizenship Law Leaves 20 Dead Amid Trump's Visit|url=https://time.com/5790831/india-hindu-muslim-clashes-trump-modi/|date=26 February 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|website=Time}}</ref> In one instance, an 85-year-old woman was burnt alive.<ref name=TIME/><ref>\nAarefa Johari, [https://scroll.in/article/954422/an-85-year-old-woman-was-burnt-to-death-in-her-home-in-delhis-gamri-extension An 85-year-old woman was burnt to death in her home in Delhi\u2019s Gamri extension], Scroll.in, 26 February 2020.\n</ref> The rioters were reported to have kept chanting \"Jai Shri Ram\" while beating their victims.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/02/25/world/asia/ap-as-trump-india-protests.html Death Toll Rises to 24 From Delhi Riots During Trump Trip], The New York Times, 25 February 2020.</ref> The police were also found to join in the chant while siding with the Hindu mobs.<ref>Kaushal Shroff, [https://caravanmagazine.in/conflict/delhi-violence-cops-shouted-jai-shri-ram-with-armed-hindu-mob-charged-at-muslims Delhi violence: Cops shouted \"Jai Shri Ram\" with armed Hindu mob, charged at Muslims], The Caravan, 25 February 2020.</ref> The Muslims were told ''Hindustan me rehna hoga, Jai Shri Ram kehna hoga'' (\"if you want to stay in India, you will have to chant Jai Shri Ram\").<ref>Kaushal Shroff, [https://caravanmagazine.in/conflict/delhi-violence-cops-shouted-jai-shri-ram-with-armed-hindu-mob-charged-at-muslims Delhi violence: Cops shouted \u201cJai Shri Ram\u201d with armed Hindu mob, charged at Muslims], The Caravan, 25 February 2020.</ref> Indian journalist [[Rana Ayyub]], writing in ''[[TIME]]'', commented that the slogan had become a \"racist [[Dog-whistle politics|dog whistle]]\" against Muslims.<ref name=TIME>\nRana Ayyub, [https://time.com/5791759/narendra-modi-india-delhi-riots-violence-muslim/ Narendra Modi Looks the Other Way as New Delhi Burns], ''TIME'', 28 February 2020.\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vishva Hindu Parishad]]\n[[Category:Sangh Parivar]]\n[[Category:Ayodhya dispute]]\n[[Category:Violence against Muslims]]\n", "name_user": "2405:204:2295:b204::22ad:c0a0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eUsage in violent incidents)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jai_Shri_Ram"}
{"title_page": "Timmy Time", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox television \n| show_name                = Timmy Time\n| image                    = Timmy Time logo.svg\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Children's television series|Children's]] [[animated series|animation]]\n| creator                  = [[Jackie Cockle]]\n| developer                = \n| based_on                 = {{based_on|''[[Shaun the Sheep]]''|[[Richard Starzak]]}}<br>{{based on|''[[Wallace & Gromit]]'' and [[A Close Shave]]|[[Nick Park]]}}\n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = \n| voices                   = [[Kate Harbour]]<br />[[Justin Fletcher]]<br />Louis Jones\n| narrated                 =  Dennis Ploughborough (2009-2015)<br>[[Harley Bird]] and [[Kathleen Herles]] (2019-present)\n| composer                 = Mike Stobbie\n| opentheme                = It's Timmy\n| endtheme                 = It\u2019s Timmy (second verse)\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 4\n| num_episodes             = 144  ([[List of Timmy Time episodes|List of episodes]])\n| producer                 = Jackie Cockle\n| company                  = [[Aardman Animations]]\n| executive_producer       = Miles Bullough<br />[[David Sproxton]]<br />[[Peter Lord]]<br />[[Nick Park]]\n| location                 = Filmed in [[Bristol]]\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 10 minutes (2009-2011)<br> 5 minutes (2019)\n| distributor              = Aardman Animations\n| network                  = [[CBeebies]]\n| picture_format          = [[PAL]] ([[1080i]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereo]]\n| first_run                = \n| first_aired              = 6 April 2009\n| last_aired               = present\n| related                  = ''[[A Close Shave]]''<br />''[[Shaun the Sheep]]''\n| website                  = http://www.timmytime.tv/\n}}\n\n'''''Timmy Time''''' is a British [[stop-motion]] [[animated]] [[children's television series]] made for the [[BBC]] by [[Aardman Animations]]. It started broadcasting in the United Kingdom on [[CBeebies]] on 6 April 2009.<ref name=\"licensing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.licensing.biz/brand-profiles/39/Timmy|title=Timmy Tales|last=Loveday|first=Samantha|publisher=Licensing.biz|accessdate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727083603/http://www.licensing.biz/brand-profiles/39/Timmy|archivedate=27 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The show is a spin-off from the ''[[Shaun the Sheep]]'' animation, in turn a spin off of the ''[[Wallace and Gromit]]'' film, ''[[A Close Shave]]'' (1995).<ref name=\"licensing\"/>\n\nThe first two series ran for 26 episodes. In the United Kingdom, the show's most recent run began in September 2011 on [[CBeebies]]. In Australia, season one commenced in May 2009 on [[ABC1]] and season three started in May 2011 on [[ABC 4 Kids]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/netw/200905/programs/ZY9763A001D22052009T082400.htm| title=ABC1 Programming Airdate: Timmy Time (E1 S1) | publisher=ABC Television Publicity | accessdate=2 August 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/abc2/201105/programs/ZX1166A001D2011-05-30T090106.htm?program=Timmy%20Time| title=ABC4Kids Programming Airdate: Timmy Time (E1 S3) | publisher=ABC Television Publicity | accessdate=2 August 2012 }}</ref> The show also broadcast reruns on [[Disney Junior]] from its launch in 2012, but the show was discontinued in May 2014.\n\n==Premise and format==\nIn this series, Timmy and his friends<ref name=\"Screenhead\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenhead.com/reviews/timmy-time-bbc-series/|title=Timmy Time BBC Series|publisher=Screenhead.com|accessdate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201110919/http://www.screenhead.com/reviews/timmy-time-bbc-series/|archivedate=1 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> have to learn to share, make friends and accept their mistakes.<ref name=\"Cbeebies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cbeebies/grownups/about/programmes/timmy.shtml|title=Timmy Time|publisher=BBC - CBeebies|accessdate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121042629/http://www.bbc.co.uk/cbeebies/grownups/about/programmes/timmy.shtml|archivedate=21 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They are supervised by two teachers, Harriet the Heron and Osbourne the Owl. The show is aimed at pre-school-aged children, which the company described as \"a natural next step for Aardman\".<ref name=\"licensing\"/>\n\nThe show is made up of ten-minute episodes, which do not feature much dialogue, much like ''[[Shaun the Sheep]]'' and ''[[Wallace and Gromit]]''. Shaun, his friends, Bitzer and the Farmer did not appear.<ref name=\"licensing\" /> A filming of one episode was featured on the [[Discovery Channel]]'s ''[[How It's Made]]''.\n\n==Elevator ==\n{{main|List of Timmy Time episodes}}\n{{:List of Timmy Time episodes}}\n\n==Characters==\n* Timmy is a male lamb who is the titular character and enjoys being in the spotlight. He is three years old in sheep years and later turns four in the episode Timmy's Birthday. In many of the episodes he gets into trouble; however, he learns from his mistakes, and often tries to help the other characters out when he can. Timmy's noise is baaa. He is best friends with Yabba, and is very close to Finlay. He also appears in Shaun the Sheep.\n* Harriet is a female pelican who speaks through caws and clicks. She is one of the two teachers. Harriet's noise is squawk.\n* Osbourne is a male owl who is the other teacher of the class and the father to Otus.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Osbourne's noise is hoot-hoot.\n* Yabba is a female duckling who is very similar to Timmy in personality and is best friends with her. Yabba's noise is quack.\n* Paxton is a male piglet who is characterised by his appetite for apples and his weight. He wears a blue sweater and is never seen without it. Paxton's noise is oink.\n* Mittens is a female kitten who is like other kittens: she hates getting her fur dirty (or wet) and is rather sensitive. Mittens's noise is mee-ew-ew. In some episodes, she seems to have feelings for Timmy. She always loves playing with picnics.\n* Ruffy is a male puppy who is energetic but he can be mentally rather slow. Ruffy's noise is rowf.\n* Apricot is a female hedgehog who is very quiet and skittish. When startled or frightened by someone or something she rolls up into a ball. Apricot's noise is hicoooo, though she rarely speaks.\n* Stripey is a male badger cub who is a bit sleepy and slow as badgers are nocturnal. Stripey's noise is eh-eh.\n* Kid is a male goat who has a large appetite like Paxton, and chews anything in sight. If the thing he is chewing is taken from him he does not mind; he just moves on to something else. Kid's noise is meh.\n* Otus is a male owlet who enjoys helping and looks up to Osbourne. He can be typically found reading and is very sensitive, sometimes copying his father Osbourne. Otus is commonly confused to be female due to his feminine voice tone and pink and purple feathers. Otus's noise is too-hoo.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* Finlay is a male fox kit who is excitable and full of energy. Finlay's noise is yip-yap.\n* Bumpy is a male green caterpillar who is not part of the class but has many background appearances in the show. Bumpy makes a soft purring noise.\n* Timmy's Mum is a female sheep who is also not part of the class, but does appear in the opening sequence, \"Timmy's Christmas Surprise\" and the end credits. She is the only parent of the show (excluding Osbourne) and also appears in Shaun The Sheep.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Timmy Time}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.timmytime.tv/}}\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{BBC Online|id=cbeebies/timmy-time|title=''Timmy Time''}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=1125758|title=Timmy Time}}\n* [http://disneyjunior.com/timmy-time Timmy Time on Disney Junior]\n\n{{Aardman Animations}}\n{{Wallace and Gromit}}\n\n[[Category:Television series by Aardman Animations]]\n[[Category:2000s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2009 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2012 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:BBC children's television programmes]]\n[[Category:British children's animated television programmes]]\n[[Category:Clay animation television series]]\n[[Category:British animated television programmes featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:British television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Wallace and Gromit]]\n[[Category:2000s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:Disney Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:British preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:Discovery Kids original programming]]\n[[Category:Treehouse TV shows]]\n[[Category:PBS Kids shows]]\n[[Category:Television series about sheep]]\n[[Category:Television series without speech]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox television \n| show_name                = Timmy Time\n| image                    = Timmy Time logo.svg\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Children's television series|Children's]] [[animated series|animation]]\n| creator                  = [[Jackie Cockle]]\n| developer                = \n| based_on                 = {{based_on|''[[Shaun the Sheep]]''|[[Richard Starzak]]}}<br>{{based on|''[[Wallace & Gromit]]'' and [[A Close Shave]]|[[Nick Park]]}}\n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = \n| voices                   = [[Kate Harbour]]<br />[[Justin Fletcher]]<br />Louis Jones\n| narrated                 =  Dennis Ploughborough (2009-2015)<br>[[Harley Bird]] and [[Kathleen Herles]] (2019-present)\n| composer                 = Mike Stobbie\n| opentheme                = It's Timmy\n| endtheme                 = It\u2019s Timmy (second verse)\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 4\n| num_episodes             = 144  ([[List of Timmy Time episodes|List of episodes]])\n| producer                 = Jackie Cockle\n| company                  = [[Aardman Animations]]\n| executive_producer       = Miles Bullough<br />[[David Sproxton]]<br />[[Peter Lord]]<br />[[Nick Park]]\n| location                 = Filmed in [[Bristol]]\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 10 minutes (2009-2011)<br> 5 minutes (2019)\n| distributor              = Aardman Animations\n| network                  = [[CBeebies]]\n| picture_format          = [[PAL]] ([[1080i]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereo]]\n| first_run                = \n| first_aired              = 6 April 2009\n| last_aired               = present\n| related                  = ''[[A Close Shave]]''<br />''[[Shaun the Sheep]]''\n| website                  = http://www.timmytime.tv/\n}}\n\n'''''Timmy Time''''' is a British [[stop-motion]] [[animated]] [[children's television series]] made for the [[BBC]] by [[Aardman Animations]]. It started broadcasting in the United Kingdom on [[CBeebies]] on 6 April 2009.<ref name=\"licensing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.licensing.biz/brand-profiles/39/Timmy|title=Timmy Tales|last=Loveday|first=Samantha|publisher=Licensing.biz|accessdate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727083603/http://www.licensing.biz/brand-profiles/39/Timmy|archivedate=27 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The show is a spin-off from the ''[[Shaun the Sheep]]'' animation, in turn a spin off of the ''[[Wallace and Gromit]]'' film, ''[[A Close Shave]]'' (1995).<ref name=\"licensing\"/>\n\nThe first two series ran for 26 episodes. In the United Kingdom, the show's most recent run began in September 2011 on [[CBeebies]]. In Australia, season one commenced in May 2009 on [[ABC1]] and season three started in May 2011 on [[ABC 4 Kids]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/netw/200905/programs/ZY9763A001D22052009T082400.htm| title=ABC1 Programming Airdate: Timmy Time (E1 S1) | publisher=ABC Television Publicity | accessdate=2 August 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/abc2/201105/programs/ZX1166A001D2011-05-30T090106.htm?program=Timmy%20Time| title=ABC4Kids Programming Airdate: Timmy Time (E1 S3) | publisher=ABC Television Publicity | accessdate=2 August 2012 }}</ref> The show also broadcast reruns on [[Disney Junior]] from its launch in 2012, but the show was discontinued in May 2014.\n\n==Premise and format==\nIn this series, Timmy and his friends<ref name=\"Screenhead\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenhead.com/reviews/timmy-time-bbc-series/|title=Timmy Time BBC Series|publisher=Screenhead.com|accessdate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201110919/http://www.screenhead.com/reviews/timmy-time-bbc-series/|archivedate=1 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> have to learn to share, make friends and accept their mistakes.<ref name=\"Cbeebies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cbeebies/grownups/about/programmes/timmy.shtml|title=Timmy Time|publisher=BBC - CBeebies|accessdate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121042629/http://www.bbc.co.uk/cbeebies/grownups/about/programmes/timmy.shtml|archivedate=21 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They are supervised by two teachers, Harriet the Heron and Osbourne the Owl. The show is aimed at pre-school-aged children, which the company described as \"a natural next step for Aardman\".<ref name=\"licensing\"/>\n\nThe show is made up of ten-minute episodes, which do not feature much dialogue, much like ''[[Shaun the Sheep]]'' and ''[[Wallace and Gromit]]''. Shaun, his friends, Bitzer and the Farmer did not appear.<ref name=\"licensing\" /> A filming of one episode was featured on the [[Discovery Channel]]'s ''[[How It's Made]]''.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Timmy Time episodes}}\n{{:List of Timmy Time episodes}}\n\n==Characters==\n* Timmy is a male lamb who is the titular character and enjoys being in the spotlight. He is three years old in sheep years and later turns four in the episode Timmy's Birthday. In many of the episodes he gets into trouble; however, he learns from his mistakes, and often tries to help the other characters out when he can. Timmy's noise is baaa. He is best friends with Yabba, and is very close to Finlay. He also appears in Shaun the Sheep.\n* Harriet is a female pelican who speaks through caws and clicks. She is one of the two teachers. Harriet's noise is squawk.\n* Osbourne is a male owl who is the other teacher of the class and the father to Otus.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Osbourne's noise is hoot-hoot.\n* Yabba is a female duckling who is very similar to Timmy in personality and is best friends with her. Yabba's noise is quack.\n* Paxton is a male piglet who is characterised by his appetite for apples and his weight. He wears a blue sweater and is never seen without it. Paxton's noise is oink.\n* Mittens is a female kitten who is like other kittens: she hates getting her fur dirty (or wet) and is rather sensitive. Mittens's noise is mee-ew-ew. In some episodes, she seems to have feelings for Timmy. She always loves playing with picnics.\n* Ruffy is a male puppy who is energetic but he can be mentally rather slow. Ruffy's noise is rowf.\n* Apricot is a female hedgehog who is very quiet and skittish. When startled or frightened by someone or something she rolls up into a ball. Apricot's noise is hicoooo, though she rarely speaks.\n* Stripey is a male badger cub who is a bit sleepy and slow as badgers are nocturnal. Stripey's noise is eh-eh.\n* Kid is a male goat who has a large appetite like Paxton, and chews anything in sight. If the thing he is chewing is taken from him he does not mind; he just moves on to something else. Kid's noise is meh.\n* Otus is a male owlet who enjoys helping and looks up to Osbourne. He can be typically found reading and is very sensitive, sometimes copying his father Osbourne. Otus is commonly confused to be female due to his feminine voice tone and pink and purple feathers. Otus's noise is too-hoo.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* Finlay is a male fox kit who is excitable and full of energy. Finlay's noise is yip-yap.\n* Bumpy is a male green caterpillar who is not part of the class but has many background appearances in the show. Bumpy makes a soft purring noise.\n* Timmy's Mum is a female sheep who is also not part of the class, but does appear in the opening sequence, \"Timmy's Christmas Surprise\" and the end credits. She is the only parent of the show (excluding Osbourne) and also appears in Shaun The Sheep.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Timmy Time}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.timmytime.tv/}}\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{BBC Online|id=cbeebies/timmy-time|title=''Timmy Time''}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=1125758|title=Timmy Time}}\n* [http://disneyjunior.com/timmy-time Timmy Time on Disney Junior]\n\n{{Aardman Animations}}\n{{Wallace and Gromit}}\n\n[[Category:Television series by Aardman Animations]]\n[[Category:2000s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2009 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2012 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:BBC children's television programmes]]\n[[Category:British children's animated television programmes]]\n[[Category:Clay animation television series]]\n[[Category:British animated television programmes featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:British television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Wallace and Gromit]]\n[[Category:2000s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:Disney Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:British preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:Discovery Kids original programming]]\n[[Category:Treehouse TV shows]]\n[[Category:PBS Kids shows]]\n[[Category:Television series about sheep]]\n[[Category:Television series without speech]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:6c32:c800:e005:372f:f5df:d51f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timmy_Time"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Negapatam (1782)", "text_new": "{{short description|Naval battle in 1782}}\n{{about|the 1782 naval action|other actions with this name|Battle of Negapatam (disambiguation)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{citation style|date=July 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2012}}\n}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{infobox military conflict\n|conflict    =Battle of Negapatam\n|partof      =the [[American Revolutionary War]]\n|image       =BattleOfNegapatamBySerres.jpg\n|image_size  =300px\n|caption     =Depiction of the battle by [[Dominic Serres]]\n|date        =6 July 1782\n|place       =[[Bay of Bengal]], off [[Negapatam]]\n|coordinates ={{coord|10|46|41|N|79|51|58|E|type:country_scale:10000000|display=inline}}\n|map_type    =\n|map_relief  =\n|latitude    =\n|longitude   =\n|map_size    =\n|map_marksize=\n|map_caption =\n|map_label   =\n|territory   =\n|result      =Tactically indecisive<ref name=\"Mackesy498\">[[#Mackesy|Mackesy p 498 (1967)]], p 498</ref><br>British strategic victory<ref name=\"Fredriksen176\">[[#Fredriksen|Fredriksen (2006)]], p 229</ref><ref name=\"Sweetman176\">[[#Sweetman|Sweetman (1997)]], p 176</ref><ref name=\"Thomas153\">[[#Thomas|Thomas (1998)]], pp. 153-54</ref>\n|status      =\n|combatant1  ={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain|23px}}\n|combatant2  ={{flagcountry|Kingdom of France|23px}}\n|commander1  =[[Edward Hughes (admiral)|Sir Edward Hughes]]\n|commander2  =[[Pierre Andre de Suffren Saint Tropez|Bailli de Suffren]]\n|units1      =\n|units2      =\n|strength1   =11 [[ships of the line]]\n|strength2   =11 ships of the line\n|casualties1 =77 killed, 233 wounded<ref name=\"Clodfelter\">[[#Clodfelter|Clodfelter (2002)]], p. 840</ref>\n|casualties2 =178 killed, 601 wounded<ref name=\"Clodfelter\"/>\n|notes       =\n|campaignbox =\n{{Campaignbox Anglo-French War (1778\u201383)}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Negapatam''' was the third in the series of battles fought between a [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] fleet, under Vice-Admiral [[Edward Hughes (admiral)|Sir Edward Hughes]], and a French fleet, under the [[Pierre Andre de Suffren Saint Tropez|Bailli de Suffren]], off the coast of [[India]] during the [[Anglo-French War (1778\u201383)|Anglo-French War]]. The battle was fought on 6 July 1782.<ref name=\"Castex269\">[[#Castex|Castex (2004)]], pp. 269\u2013272</ref> The battle was indecisive but Suffren was thwarted in his goal by Hughes and withdrew to [[Cuddalore]], while the British remained in control of Negapatam.<ref name=\"Fredriksen176\"/><ref name=\"Sweetman176\"/>\n\n== Background ==\nFrance had entered the [[American Revolutionary War]] in 1778, and Britain declared war on the [[Dutch Republic]] in late 1780, after the Dutch refused to stop trading in military supplies with the French and the Americans. The British had rapidly gained control over most French and Dutch outposts in India when news of these events reached India, spawning the [[Second Anglo-Mysore War]] in the process. [[Negapatam]] was [[Siege of Negapatam|sieged and taken]] by [[Hector Munro, 8th laird of Novar|Sir Hector Munro]] in November 1781.\n\nThe French admiral the Bailli de Suffren was dispatched on a mission to provide military assistance to French colonies in [[India]]. He arrived in February 1782, and immediately engaged the British fleet of Vice-Admiral Sir Edward Hughes in the inconclusive [[Battle of Sadras]]. After both fleets spent time in port repairing, refitting, and re-provisioning, they met again in the April [[Battle of Providien]], south of the [[Ceylon]]ese port of [[Trincomalee]], that was ended by a storm and then nightfall. Hughes put into Trincomalee, a formerly Dutch port the British [[Capture of Trincomalee|had captured]] in January, for repairs, while Suffren went to the Dutch-controlled port of [[Batticaloa]].\n\nWhile at Batticaloa, Suffren received dispatches from the \u00cele de France (now [[Mauritius]]) that ordered him to return there to escort additional French troops to India. He chose not to do so, citing the parity between the two fleets, and the need to defend French troops already on the ground in India against the movements of the British fleet.\n\nThe French, with about 2,000 effective troops under the command of Comte du Chemin, had captured [[Cuddalore]] on 6 May. [[Hyder Ali]], the ruler of [[Kingdom of Mysore|Mysore]], originally wanted the French to take the more important port of Negapatam. The French joined with Hyder's army of 60,000 to lay siege to the British at [[Vandavasi]]. When the British sent an army of 12,000 toward Vandavasi to relieve the siege, du Chemin, against the wishes of Hyder, refused to engage in a battle that the Franco-Mysorean force would probably have won (which would have significantly reduced the British military presence in India). As a result, Hyder lifted the siege and retreated to the vicinity of [[Pondicherry (city)|Pondicherry]].\n\nHyder Ali learned of Suffren's actions in the first two battles with Hughes, and sent a message to Suffren to arrange a meeting. Suffren had in the meantime sailed from Batticaloa to do the job that du Chemin would not: capture Negapatam. He stopped at Cuddalore on 20 June to take on troops and supplies for the attack, which he hoped to do by surprise. When he was ready to sail he learned that Hughes had sailed past, apparently also en route to Negapatam. As his fleet had grown by captured prizes and arrivals from \u00cele de France (it was now twelve [[ships of the line]] and four frigates), Suffren gave chase and caught up with Hughes, who had anchored off Negapatam, on 5 July.\n\n== Battle ==\n[[File:SouthIndia1794.jpeg|thumb|right|Detail of a 1794 map of south India and Ceylon. Batticaloa is north of the southeastern point of Ceylon]]\n\nSuffren was in the process of forming his battle line around 3&nbsp;pm when a [[squall]] took down the main and mizzen top masts of [[French ship Ajax (1779)|''Ajax'']], under [[Ren\u00e9 Joseph Bouvet de Pr\u00e9court|Bouvet-Pr\u00e9court]], forcing her to drop out of his line.{{sfnp|Roche|2005|p=28}}  When the squall calmed, the breeze was to Hughes' advantage so he sailed from his anchorage at the harbour of Negapatam. The two fleets spent the night anchored two cannonshots apart.\n\nThe next morning, Suffren was infuriated to learn that repairs had not been made to ''Ajax'', and that her captain wanted to retreat. Given that battle was imminent, Suffren refused. He then ordered his line to bear down on the British line for close action. As they began to move, ''Ajax'' stood away and did not join the action. At 9:30&nbsp;am on 6 July, the fleets opened fire on each other, first at long range. ''Flamand'' engaged ''Hero'' and ''Exeter'', ''Annibal'' engaged ''Isis'', ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'' faced ''Burford'', and ''Brillant'' opposed ''Sultan'' while the two flagships, ''H\u00e9ros'' and ''Superb'', did battle with each other. The remainder of the British line was not able to directly line up against the French, resulting in an angle in their line where ''Sphinx'' and ''Monarca'' battled that minimized the action between the ships at the end of the line. ''Flamand'' took significant damage, but was able to return the favour to its opponents. ''Brillant'' began to suffer under the fire of ''Sultan'', but Suffren managed to detach from ''H\u00e9ros'' to come to her rescue.\n\nThe battle proceeded with vigour until about 1&nbsp;pm, when the wind suddenly changed, throwing both lines into confusion. With the wind head-on to the two parallel lines of ships, some ships turned to starboard and some to port.<ref name=ClowesIIIp556>[[#Clowes|Clowes (Vol.III)]], p.556</ref> The majority turned away from the engagement but six ships, four British and two French, turned in towards one another. The four British ships were the fourth, fifth, eighth and tenth in line, respectively ''Burford'', ''Sultan'', ''Worcester'' and ''Eagle''; the two French were ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'' (third in line) and towards the rear of the line ''Brillant'', which was dismasted by this stage. ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'' was engaged by ''Sultan'' and \"two other ships\", and escaped through the arrival of Suffren in his flagship and the filling of her sails as she fell off to starboard, while ''Brillant'' was fired on by ''Worcester'' and ''Eagle'', and was also rescued by the approach of Suffren's ship, though not before the loss of over a third of her complement dead or wounded.<ref name=ClowesIIIp556/>\n\nWith occasional meetings between two ships, Hughes attempted to reform his line around 2&nbsp;pm, but neither fleet was in a state to adopt battle positions easily, so Suffren decided to draw away downwind, to the north, toward Cuddalore. One British observer noted that \"our fleet was utterly incapable of preventing or pursuing them\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moir |first1=John |title=Transactions in India |date=1786 |publisher=John Debrett |page=[https://archive.org/details/transactionsini01moirgoog/page/n477 470] |url=https://archive.org/details/transactionsini01moirgoog |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nSuffren had been thwarted in his efforts to take to Negapatam<ref name=\"Thomas153\"/> \u2013 he stripped M. Bouvet, the captain of ''Ajax'', of his command, and arrested three others for a variety of transgressions in this battle and the previous two. One of those arrested, M. de Cillart, commander of ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'', had started to [[striking the colors|strike his colors]] during one of the post-squall engagements, but his subordinates prevented the act.<ref name=\"Thomas153\"/> Suffren then sailed for Cuddalore to effect repairs. Hughes spent the next two weeks at sea, only returning to [[Chennai|Madras]] for repairs on 20 July. Negapatam would remain in British hands until the end of the war. At the [[Treaty of Paris (1783)]] the Dutch Republic would cede Negapatam to Britain.\n\n== Order of battle ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n!colspan=\"11\" bgcolor=\"white\"|French line of battle {{sfnp|Cunat|1852|p=169}}\n|- valign=\"top\"|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n! width=12%; align= center rowspan=2 | <small> Ship </small>\n! width=15%; align= center rowspan=2 | <small> Rate </small>\n! width=5%; align= center rowspan=2 | <small> Guns </small>\n! width=5%; align= center rowspan=2 | <small> Navy </small>\n! width=22%; align= center rowspan=2 | <small> Commander </small>\n! width=15%; align= center colspan=3 | <small>Casualties</small>\n! width=25%; align= center rowspan=2 | <small>Notes</small>\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n! width=5%; align= center  | <small> Killed </small>\n! width=5%; align= center  | <small> Wounded </small>\n! width=5%; align= center  | <small> Total</small>\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| align= left    | ''[[French ship Flamand|Flamand]]''\n| align= center  | 54-gun\n| align= center  | 54\n| align= center  | [[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|45px|Ensign of the French Royal Navy]]\n| align= left    | Captain [[Louis-Hyacinte de Cavelier de Cuverville|de Cuverville]]\n| align= right   | 13\n| align= right   | 56\n| align= right   | 69 {{sfnp|Cunat|1852|p=171}}\n| align= left    |\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| align= left    | ''[[French ship Annibal (1779)|Annibal]]''\n| align= center  | [[74-gun]]\n| align= center  | 74\n| align= center  | [[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|45px|Ensign of the French Royal Navy]]\n| align= left    | Captain [[Bernard Boudin de Tromelin]]\n| align= right   | 28\n| align= right   | 80\n| align= right   | 108\n| align= left    | lieutenant de fr\u00e9gate de Rigny wounded {{sfnp|Cunat|1852|p=170}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| align= left    | [[French ship S\u00e9v\u00e8re (1778)|''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'']]\n| align= center  | 64-gun\n| align= center  | 64\n| align= center  | [[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|45px