ng the Past: Ancient Rome, Cinema and History|publisher=Routledge, 2013|isbn=1317796071}}</ref> The rights of film's negatives and copies were bought by the producers of [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s 1960 film ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'', as to prevent eventual new releases of the film that could have damaged the commercial outcome of Kubrik's film; this resulted in ''Sins of Rome'''s withdrawal from market for about thirty years.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Silke Knippschild, Marta Garcia Morcillo|title=Seduction and Power: Antiquity in the Visual and Performing Arts|publisher=A&amp;C Black, 2013|isbn=1441190651}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n\n*[[Massimo Girotti]] as [[Spartacus]]\n*[[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]] as Amitis\n*[[Gianna Maria Canale]] as Sabina\n*[[Yves Vincent]] as Ocnomas\n*[[Carlo Ninchi]] as [[Marcus Licinius Crassus]]\n*[[Carlo Giustini]] as Artorige\n*[[Teresa Franchini]] as  Spartacus's Mother\n*[[Vittorio Sanipoli]] as Marcus Virilius Rufus \n*[[Umberto Silvestri]] as  [[Lentulus]] \n*[[Renato Baldini]] as  Gladiator \n*[[Nerio Bernardi]]  \n*[[Cesare Bettarini]]\n\n==Release==\n''Sins of Rome'' was distributed in Italy as ''Spartaco'' by A.P.I. on January 28, 1953.{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}} The film grossed a total of 450 million [[Italian lire]] in Italy.{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}} The film was released in the United States as ''Sins of Rome'' and in the United Kingdom as ''Spartacus the Gladiator''.{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0045183}}\n{{Spartacus}}\n{{Riccardo Freda}}\n\n[[Category:1953 films]]\n[[Category:1950s historical films]]\n[[Category:Peplum films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Riccardo Freda]]\n[[Category:Films about gladiatorial combat]]\n[[Category:Films about rebels]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1st century BC]]\n[[Category:Films set in ancient Rome]]\n[[Category:Films set in Capua]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rome]]\n[[Category:Third