{"title_page": "Harris Scarfe", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Advert|date=September 2019}}\n{{COI|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Harris Scarfe\n| logo                = HarrisScarfe.svg\n| type                = Retail, eCommerce\n| fate                = [[Administration (law)|Receivers and Managers]] appointed\n| founded             = {{start date and age|1849}}\n| founders            = George Peter Harris and John C. Lanyon\n| location_city       = [[Richmond, Victoria|Richmond]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| location_country    = Australia\n| location            = <!--modifies \"Head Office\" entry-->\n| industry            = [[Retail]]\n| locations           = 45 stores (February 2020)\n| products            = Bed linen, homewares, kitchenware, manchester, electrical goods, kitchen appliances, women's and men's apparel, intimates, footwear and luggage\n| num_employees       = 1200 ({{as of|2020|04|lc=y}})\n| parent              = {{unbulleted list|Greenlit Brands (2014 - November 2019)|Allegro Funds (since November 2019)}}\n| homepage            = {{url|harrisscarfe.com.au}}\n}}\n'''Harris Scarfe''' is an Australian retailer that sells bed linen, kitchenware, homewares, electrical appliances and apparel. It is headquartered in Melbourne. It has a growing e-commerce retail presence in Australia and is considered a multi-channel department store retailer.\n\nFounded in 1849, Harris Scarfe currently operates 66 retail stores nationally in two formats including \"Harris Scarfe\" [[department stores]] and \"Harris Scarfe Home\" homewares and kitchenware stores.\n\nIn December 2019, Harris Scarfe entered into voluntary administration after 170 years in operation. {{as of|2020|1}}, 21 of its 65 stores are set to close.\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\nHarris Scarfe traces its history to 10 February 1849, when the founding partners, George Peter Harris and John C. Lanyon, arrived in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]] on the ship, \"Candahar\", to establish a hardware and [[ironmonger]]y business. Lanyon left the partnership on 22 February 1855 and returned to London, where he subsequently opened up a buying house for Geo. P Harris and other businesses in South Australia. Additional partners, George Scarfe and Richard Smith, joined the business in 1866 and the business name \"Geo. P. Harris, Scarfe & Co.\" was adopted in December that year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207681585 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Adelaide Express]] |volume=IV |issue=914 |location=South Australia |date=17 December 1866 |accessdate=22 October 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nHarris Scarfe grew to become a major supplier of a broad range of household, agricultural and industrial items.  Besides conducting its retailing businesses, Harris Scarfe manufactured leather goods, including saddlery and luggage, as part of a wholesaling operation. Notably, during [[World War II]], when the [[Australian Government]] enforced price controls, it used the Harris Scarfe catalogue as the price guide.\n\n===1970s - 1980s===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2019}}\nIn 1971, Baradeen Quest Pty Limited, a subsidiary of Investment and Merchant Finance Corporation Limited (\"IMFC\") made a successful takeover bid for Harris Scarfe Limited, which was listed on the [[Australian Stock Exchange]] at the time.\n\n[[Charles Davis Limited]], a listed [[Tasmania]]n company controlled by [[Sir Donald Trescowthick]], acquired control of Harris Scarfe in 1976. Trescowthick focussed Harris Scarfe's activities on its retailing business, developing a full line department store model, while the industrial products outlet at [[Mile End, South Australia|Mile End]] evolved to become Harry's, a large hardware retailing business.\n\nThe success of Harry's led Harris Scarfe's parent company, Charles Davis Limited, to acquire other hardware retailers, including Lloyd's in South Australia, [[Campbell's]] in Queensland, and [[Bunnings Warehouse|McEwans]] in Victoria and New South Wales. In 1989, these hardware businesses were sold in a management buyout, and acquired by [[Bunnings]] in 1993.\n\n===1990s===\nIn the 1990s, Harris Scarfe entered an era of unprecedented national growth. It expanded beyond its large department store in Rundle Mall into smaller format suburban and regional shopping stores. Harris Scarfe also acquired full-line department store sites from other retailers who were rationalising their store networks including [[David Jones Limited|David Jones]], [[Myer]], John Martins, Stirling and Centre Fair. By 1995, Harris Scarfe had become Australia's third largest department store retailer, with 38 stores, and trading in all states of Australia.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe company ran into trouble during the late 1990s due to rising debts and management issues.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} In April 2001, the business was placed in receivership. Unsecured creditors were owed $93 million, and the company was $50 million in debt.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/former-harris-scarfe-executive-jailed-six-years-20020627-gduc7w.html|title=Former Harris Scarfe executive jailed six years|date=27 June 2002|work=[[The Age]]|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|agency=[[Australian Associated Press]]}}</ref> In June 2002, the company's former chief financial officer, Alan Hodgson, was sentenced to six years in jail, on multiple counts that included giving false information to the [[Australian Securities Exchange|ASX]], and failing to act honestly as a company officer.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2001, Harris Scarfe listed on the [[Australian Securities Exchange]] (ASX). In the same year, the company fell $160 million into debt, resulting in the owners, the Trescowthick family, losing $31.5 million. The government initially considered pressing charges against chairman Adam Trescowthick, but later dropped the case.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2002, the company started a revitalisation program. The store network was remodelled with new products, layouts and new branding. As a result, Harris Scarfe soon began to enjoy record growth. By 2007, Sydney-based Momentum Private Equity acquired an $80&nbsp;million majority stake in the company. During 2012, Momentum Corporate ten sold the business to [[Pepkor]], a South African private equity firm.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOver a six-month period at the end of 2003, Harris Scarfe made certain representations on a number of items in its catalogues in relation to pricing. Harris Scarfe admitted to the Australian Competition and Consumer Commission (ACCC) that representations in its promotional advertising may have misled consumers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accc.gov.au/media-release/harris-scarfe-admits-sale-prices-may-have-misled-issues-public-apology|title=Harris Scarfe admits sale prices may have misled, issues public apology|last=Commission|first=Australian Competition and Consumer|date=2013-02-23|website=Australian Competition and Consumer Commission|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nAgain in 2007 Harris Scarfe was investigated by the Australian consumer watchdog who sued the department store in the Australian Federal Court over allegedly false promotions for its sales in October 2006. The ACCC alleged that the advertising was misleading because Harris Scarfe was not offering what it advertised:\n\n# A discount off all goods in its stores.\n# A minimum of 20% off all goods in its stores.\n\nThe ACCC also alleged that the catalogue included images of products under banners stating a specific discount when some of those goods were not discounted by the stated percentage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcompany.com.au/marketing/advertising/accc-challenges-harris-scarfe-ads/|title=ACCC challenges Harris Scarfe ads|date=2007-10-12|website=SmartCompany|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the Federal Court, Adelaide has declared that Harris Scarfe Australia Pty Ltd misled consumers by representing in a catalogue that certain advertised items were discounted by a specific amount when in fact they were discounted by less than that amount, or were not discounted at all.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accc.gov.au/media-release/court-declares-harris-scarfe-misled-consumers|title=Court declares Harris Scarfe misled consumers|last=Commission|first=Australian Competition and Consumer|date=2013-02-23|website=Australian Competition and Consumer Commission|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHarris Scarfe CEO Robert Atkins, resigned from the top post at Harris Scarfe in March 2009 after eight years leading the turnaround of department store.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/exharris-scarfe-boss-robert-atkins-dies-20100115-mb6b.html|title=Ex-Harris Scarfe boss Robert Atkins dies|date=2010-01-15|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> He played a significant role in the restructuring of retail trading hours in South Australia and in the revitalisation of the state\u2019s premium retail precinct as chairman of the Rundle Mall Management Authority.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.retailbiz.com.au/offline-retailing/former-harris-scarfe-ceo-robert-atkins-dies/|title=Former Harris Scarfe CEO Robert Atkins dies|last=retailbizc0rD8|date=2010-01-15|website=retailbiz|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Robert Atkins passed away in January 2010.\n\nAfter Robert Atkins successful tenure leading Harris Scarfe, Joe Barberis was named managing director of the retailer in February 2009 until September 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.linkedin.com/in/joe-barberis-b3a2b96|title=Joe Barberis LinkedIn|last=Barberis|first=Joe|date=11 April 2020|website=LinkedIn|url-status=live}}</ref> Graham Dean, previously Myer group general manager of Electrical was named CEO of Harris Scarfe.\n\nIn 2012, Kyly Clarke became the face of Harris Scarfe's fashion home brand 'Boutique@hs'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.popsugar.com.au/fashion/Kyly-Clarke-Face-New-Harris-Scarfe-Fashion-Label-Boutiquehs-25432051|title=Kyly Clarke Is The Face of New Label Boutique@hs!|last=Rota|first=Genevieve|date=2012-10-14|website=POPSUGAR Fashion Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, Greenlit Brands, formerly [[Steinhoff International|Steinhoff Asia Pacific]], acquired [[Pepkor]] and this included Harris Scarfe. Harris Scarfe has been owned by Greenlit Brands since this time.<ref>https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/25/steinhoff-international-to-buy-pepkor-of-south-africa-for-5-7-billion/</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, General Manager of Harris Scarfe Daniel Nikoleaff was demoted to Area Manager of South Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.linkedin.com/in/daniel-nikoleaff-29325842|title=Daniel Nikoleaff - LinkedIn|last=Nikoleaff|first=Daniel|date=April 2020|website=LinkedIn|url-status=live}}</ref> Nikoleaff was replaced by Rebecca Peterson previously CEO of Lovisa jewellery stores.\n\nIn October 2013, Harris Scarfe officially launched Simply Vera,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.harrisscarfe.com.au/hs/Brands/Simply-Vera-Vera-Wang/SVVW | title=Simply Vera Vera Wang | accessdate=2020-03-03 }}</ref> by Vera Wang which is designed by [[Vera Wang]] who is based in [[New York City]]. The collection comprises a range of contemporary women's fashion, accessories, bed and bath collections and home fragrances.\n\nHarris Scarfe's home brand 'Bulls Head' Jeans were found to have harmful Azo dyes, which expert authorities classify as carcinogens. The Jeans were recalled in July 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.productsafety.gov.au/recall/harris-scarfe-pty-ltd-bulls-head-men-s-black-regular-short-leg-jeans|title=Harris Scarfe Pty Ltd\u2014Bulls Head Men\u2019s Black Regular & Short Leg Jeans|last=Australia|first=Product Safety|date=2016-07-28|website=Product Safety Australia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Harris Scarfe also collaborated with [[Shayna Blaze]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.harrisscarfe.com.au/hs/Brands/Shaynna-Blaze/SHYB | title=Shayna Blaze | accessdate=2020-03-03 }}</ref> an interior designer from [[The Block (Australian TV series)|The Block]] on bed linens, homewares, accessories and apparel.\n\nIn October 2017,  just before the Steinhoff corruption scandal unfolded, Steinhoff International appointed former The Good Guys boss Michael Ford, to oversee its Australasian operation. He had left behind a retailer that had to be significantly restructured due to cash flow problems and a lack of stock in the business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnews.com.au/insight-harris-scarfe-liquidation-dodgy-deal-or-acceptable-stitch-up-by-allegro-funds-suppliers-angry/|title=INSIGHT: Harris Scarfe Liquidation, \u2018Dodgy Deal\u2019 Or Acceptable \u2018Stitch Up\u2019 By Allegro Funds, Suppliers Angry \u2013 channelnews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\nBritish Fashion brand Debenhams granted exclusivity to Harris Scarfe for their launch in Australia in February 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hub.harrisscarfe.com.au/fashion/big-british-brands-from-debenhams-exclusive-to-us/|title=Big British Brands From Debenhams, Exclusive To Us.|date=2017-02-09|website=Harris Scarfe|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The arrangement was short lived and Harris Scarfe parted ways with Debenhams in November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/best-and-less-harris-scarfe-back-in-australian-hands-20191118-p53bp2.html|title=Best & Less, Harris Scarfe back in Australian hands|last=Powell|first=Dominic|date=2019-11-19|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nDuring April 2018, they launched a new collection with [[Jamie Durie]], TV personality [[The Outdoor Room]] named Jamie Durie by Ardor<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.harrisscarfe.com.au/hs/Brands/JAMIE-DURIE/JDUR | title=Jamie Durie | accessdate=2020-03-03 }}</ref> which is a casual bed linen product range.\n\nChannel Seven Morning Show presenter Kylie Gillies was named Harris Scarfe's fashion ambassador in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hub.harrisscarfe.com.au/whats-new/our-newest-fashion-ambassador/|title=Our newest fashion ambassador|date=2018-08-07|website=Harris Scarfe|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, parent company Greenlit Brands sold both Harris Scarfe and [[Best & Less]] to Australian private equity firm Allegro Funds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/best-and-less-harris-scarfe-back-in-australian-hands-20191118-p53bp2.html|title=Best & Less, Harris Scarfe back in Australian hands|last=Powell|first=Dominic|date=19 November 2019|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insideretail.com.au/news/greenlit-brands-offloads-best-less-harris-scarfe-and-debenhams-201911|title=Greenlit Brands offloads Best & Less, Harris Scarfe and Debenhams|last=McIlvaine|first=Heather|date=19 November 2019|work=Inside Retail|access-date=21 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/retail/greenlit-brands-harris-scarfe-best-and-less-sold-to-allegro-20191118-p53bgk|title=Greenlit Brands' Harris Scarfe, Best & Less sold to Allegro|last=Mitchell|first=Sue|date=18 November 2019|work=[[Australian Financial Review]]|access-date=11 December 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 - 2020: Voluntary administration, Trading Insolvent and Supplier Scandal  ===\nOn 11 December 2019, Harris Scarfe under General Manager Rebecca Peterson,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.linkedin.com/in/rebecca-peterson-88389255|title=LinkedIn Profile|last=Peterson|first=Rebecca|date=2 April 2020|website=LinkedIn|url-status=live}}</ref> entered voluntary administration, with Deloitte Restructuring Services partners taking over management of the business. The retailer reported $380 million in annual sales earlier in the year. At the time, Harris Scarfe had 66 stores employing 1800 staff.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/harris-scarfe-collapses-into-voluntary-administration-66-stores-in-jeopardy/6af1f6ab-f81e-4a8b-a8ec-c3f124c44e43|title=Aussie retailer Harris Scarfe collapses after 170 years in business|last=Marsh|first=Stuart|date=11 December 2019|work=[[Nine News]]|access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/harris-scarfe-department-chain-in-receivership-in-horror-year-for-retailers-20191211-p53iy8.html|title=Harris Scarfe department chain enters receivership in horror year for retailers|last=Cummins|first=Carolyn|date=11 December 2019|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref> In response, the [[Shop, Distributive and Allied Employees Association]] labour union said that they would be filing a complaint with the [[Fair Work Commission]] because they were not informed in advance. Deloitte claims Harris Scarfe has \"more than sufficient\" assets to pay all staff entitlements.<ref name=\":0\" /> In January 2020, Harris Scarfe announced it would close 21 of its 65 stores, resulting in the loss of 440 jobs. 1380 staff would remain in the 44 stores still in operation.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.insideretail.com.au/news/harris-scarfe-closing-21-stores-202001|title=Harris Scarfe closing 21 stores|last=Blake|first=Dean|date=6 January 2020|work=Inside Retail|access-date=21 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The closures consist of one in [[South Australia]] and in the [[Australian Capital Territory]], two in [[Western Australia]], three in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], six in [[Queensland]], and eight in [[New South Wales]], all due to close within four weeks.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/retail/440-jobs-21-stores-to-go-at-harris-scarfe-20200106-p53pan|title=440 jobs, 21 stores to go at Harris Scarfe|last=Baird|first=Lucas|date=6 January 2020|work=[[Australian Financial Review]]|access-date=21 January 2020|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> As of 2 February 2020, 20 stores have closed, with the store in Earlville, Cairns, being spared from closure, leaving 45 stores, being 3 in Australian Capital Territory, 3 in Queensland, 5 in Tasmania, 5 in New South Wales, 8 in South Australia and 21 in Victoria.\n\nDuring this time Harris Scarfe's credit card services and interest free offers were no longer honoured or available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cards.harrisscarfe.com.au/harris-scarfe-value-plus-card-currently-unavailable/|title=Harris Scarfe Value Plus Card: Currently Unavailable \u2013 Harris Scarfe Value Plus Credit Cards|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March 2020, it was announced that fabric and home fitting store [[Spotlight]] will purchase the remaining stores.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/spotlight-set-to-save-harris-scarfe-from-collapse-20200303-p546bm.html | title=Spotlight set to save Harris Scarfe from collapse | work=The Sydney Morning Herald| first=Dominic | last=Powell | date=2020-03-03 | accessdate=2020-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://indaily.com.au/news/business/2020/03/03/spotlight-wins-right-to-buy-harris-scarfe/ | title=Spotlight wins right to buy Harris Scarfe | work=InDaily | first=Bension | last=Siebert | date=2020-03-03 | accessdate=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2020 Harris Scarfe layed off a further 59 staff. Announced the day after Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison announced the national JobKeeper Scheme. Deloitte, which acted as Harris Scarfe\u2019s receiver, expects the sale to be finalised just after Easter. Staff were initially told the redundancies were being made due to the current economic conditions and COVID-19 crisis. This was later backtracked to claim the redundancies were part of the sale process. And that, while Harris Scarfe will be applying for the Government\u2019s JobKeeper initiative to support remaining staff, those let go on 'restructuring' grounds may not be supported under the payment scheme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideretail.com.au/news/harris-scarfe-lays-off-59-staff-offers-referrals-to-centrelink-202004|title=Harris Scarfe lays off 59 staff, offers referrals to Centrelink|date=2020-04-01|website=Inside Retail|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2020, Smart Company reported Harris Scarfe were being investigated by the retail Union for possibly breaching the Fair Work Act and treating their staff unfairly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcompany.com.au/industries/retail/harris-scarfe-workers-redundancy/|title=Harris Scarfe workers outraged as receivers make 59 staff redundant the day after wage subsidy announcement|date=2020-04-03|website=SmartCompany|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nThe Mercury newspaper in Tasmania reported on 7 April 2020, Harris Scarfe's newly renovated Hobart store would be closing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themercury.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TMWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.themercury.com.au%2Fnews%2Ftasmania%2Fharris-scarfes-hobart-store-will-close-its-doors-in-the-near-future%2Fnews-story%2Fb7e3d36a22ebcff571f34e977eb0929a&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=bc6fff70f9d21ef3a83df3c1de171760-1586612184|title=Subscribe to The Mercury|website=www.themercury.com.au|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntnews.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=NTWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ntnews.com.au%2Fnews%2Fharris-scarfes-hobart-store-will-close-its-doors-in-the-near-future%2Fnews-story%2Fb7e3d36a22ebcff571f34e977eb0929a&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=5cc4bb36e468ae699f905582f05b7ca3-1586612247|title=Subscribe to the NT News|website=www.ntnews.com.au|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Australian financial review reported on 8 April 2020 that Harris Scarfe was still in the red despite Spotlight deal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/retail/harris-scarfe-creditors-in-the-red-despite-spotlight-deal-20200408-p54i9b|title=Harris Scarfe creditors in the red despite Spotlight deal|date=2020-04-08|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> On 9 April 2020 Channel News added \"Several appliance and CE distributors are set to only get between 1.3\u00a2 and 20.5\u00a2 in the dollar under a proposed deed of company arrangement for the failed Harris Scarfe, Allegro the Company who owned the stores for only three weeks will get $70M...The Australian Financial Review reported that the receivers blamed Harris Scarfe\u2019s collapse on loss-making stores, most of which opened between 2014 and 2019, and the retailer\u2019s inability to access funding after the sale to Allegro, which is the first ranking secured creditor and will receive a return of almost $70 million.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnews.com.au/harris-scarfe-ce-appliance-suppliers-set-to-only-get-cents-but-5-week-owner-gets-70m/|title=Harris Scarfe CE & Appliance Suppliers Set To Only Get Cents But 5 Week Owner Gets $70M \u2013 channelnews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24th 2020, The Herald Sun reported Harris Scarfe became insolvent the moment private equity firm Allegro Funds took control of the struggling department store chain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=HSWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.heraldsun.com.au%2Fbusiness%2Fharris-scarfe-claim-insolvent-from-the-word-go%2Fnews-story%2F55e2a428728d413890655dfd8bccf7d3&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=e9fb864dbad35e955f5d8702972638da-1588158889|title=Heraldsun.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to the Herald Sun for exclusive stories|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> Days later Channel News had spoken to unhappy suppliers who were allegedly ripped off and believe the company's collapse was an orchestrated con.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnews.com.au/insight-harris-scarfe-liquidation-dodgy-deal-or-acceptable-stitch-up-by-allegro-funds-suppliers-angry/|title=INSIGHT: Harris Scarfe Liquidation, \u2018Dodgy Deal\u2019 Or Acceptable \u2018Stitch Up\u2019 By Allegro Funds, Suppliers Angry \u2013 channelnews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> Channel News in a follow up reported Harris Scarfe had illegally traded insolvent during December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnews.com.au/ripped-off-insolvent-harris-scarfe-allegro-funds-deal-looks-like-another-dick-smith-anchorage-capital-saga/|title=\u201cRipped Off\u201d Insolvent Harris Scarfe Allegro Funds Deal, Looks Like Another Dick Smith Anchorage Capital Saga \u2013 channelnews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> \n\nCommercial Real Estate reported on April 28th 2020 that Harris Scarfe's new owner Spotlight refused to pay its monthly rent for all stores. They were unwilling to work with landlords, demanding a 50% reduction on all rent. Spotlight also had yet to pay $50 million for the newly acquired Harris Scarfe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commercialrealestate.com.au/news/spotlight-halts-april-rent-demands-50pc-cut-951705/|title=Spotlight halts April rent, demands 50pc cut|last=Schlesinger|first=Larry|date=2020-04-28|website=Commercial Real Estate|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> Former Queensland Premier Campbell Newman described Spotlight's actions as: \u201cunconscionable conduct...Many landlords have received \u2018take it or leave it\u2019 letters proposing significant rent concessions or outright rent waivers. Landlords are reporting that they have been threatened and pressured to accept...\u201cAt the same time, many of these companies have actually seen improved sales turnover.\u201d Mr Newman said.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commercialrealestate.com.au/news/spotlight-halts-april-rent-demands-50pc-cut-951705/|title=Spotlight halts April rent, demands 50pc cut|last=Schlesinger|first=Larry|date=2020-04-28|website=Commercial Real Estate|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> \n\nAs of April 2020, approximately 1200 staff remain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcompany.com.au/industries/retail/harris-scarfe-workers-redundancy/|title=Harris Scarfe workers outraged as receivers make 59 staff redundant the day after wage subsidy announcement|date=2020-04-03|website=SmartCompany|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Store formats==\n'''Harris Scarfe department stores''' sell a full range of bed linen, homewares, cookware, manchester, apparel, electrical appliances, kitchen appliances, menswear, womenswear, intimates, sportswear, travel and outdoor. There are currently 40 Harris Scarfe stores.\n\n'''Harris Scarfe Home''' stores sell homewares including bed linen, homewares, cookware, kitchen appliances, electrical goods, personal care and bathroom electrical. There are currently five Harris Scarfe Home stores.\n\n== Product categories ==\nHarris Scarfe stores sell the following products:\n* Bed Linen & Manchester \u2013 bedding, linen, towels, manchester, pillows, decorative cushions\n* Homewares \u2013 crockery, cutlery, glassware, food preparation\n* Kitchenware and Cookware  \u2013 cook sets, fry pans, cast iron \n* Personal Care & Bathroom Electrical \u2013 hairdryers, shavers\n* Kitchen Appliances \u2013 kettles, toasters, food processors, blenders\n* Electrical Appliances - heaters, fans, cookers, grills, toasters \n* Clothing and Apparel - womenswear, menswear\n* Travel \u2013 luggage, accessories\n\n==Exclusive brands==\n\n=== Smith + Nobel ===\nSmith + Nobel is Harris Scarfe's budget home brand. The Smith + Nobel name is used across Manchester, Homewares and Electrical. A majority of Harris Scarfe's stock is under the Smith + Nobel name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harrisscarfe.com.au/search?text=smith+and+nobel|title=Search smith and nobel {{!}} HS Site|website=www.harrisscarfe.com.au|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Simply Vera \u2013 Vera Wang ===\nIn October 2013, Harris Scarfe were officially launched<ref>{{cite web |url = http://graciousmagazine.blogspot.com.au/2013/09/simply-vera-vera-wang-for-harris-scarfe.html |title = Simply Vera \u2013 Vera Wang for Harris Scarfe |date = 25 September 2013 |author= Sweaty Betty PR |publisher = Gracious Magazine}}</ref> as the only Australian retailer allowed to sell the Simply Vera range<ref>{{cite web |url = http://fashioninitiative.com.au/fashion/simply-vera-vera-wang-sold-collaborates-with-heritage-department-store-harris-scarfe/ |title = Simply Vera \u2013 Vera Wang collaborates with heritage department store Harris Scarfe. |date = 22 October 2013 |first = Phoebes |last = Garland  |publisher = fashioninitiative.com.au }}</ref> designed by [[Vera Wang]] who is based in [[New York City]]. The collection comprises a range of contemporary women's fashion, accessories, bed and bath collections & home fragrance.\n\n=== Shayna Blaze ===\nShayna Blaze homewares collection<ref>{{cite web |url = http://fortemag.com.au/?p=34955 |title = Shayna Blaze for Harris Scarfe |date = 18 October 2017 |author= Forte Magazine |publisher = Forte Magazine }}</ref> designed by [[Shayna Blaze]].  The collection includes bed linen, homewares and apparel.\n\n=== Jamie Durie - By Ardor ===\nJamie Durie homewares collection<ref>{{cite web |url = https://hub.harrisscarfe.com.au/home/the-art-of-bringing-the-outdoors-in-with-jamie-durie-by-ardor/ |title = The Art of bringing the outdoors in with Jamie Durie by Ardor |date = 16 April 2018 |author= Harris Scarfe |publisher = hub Harris Scarfe }}</ref> designed by [[Jamie Durie]].  The collection includes casual bed linens, cushions and sheet sets that are designed to bring nature inside the home.\n\n=== MOZI ===\nMOZI is a Melbourne-based lifestyle brand specialising in unique Australian designed homewares, lifestyle and bath & body products.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.houzz.com.au/professionals/furniture-and-accessories/mozi-australia-pfvwau-pf~1763424851 |title = MOZI Lifestyle Brand Exclusively at Harris Scarfe |date = 20 October 2018 |author= Houzz |publisher = hub Houzz }}</ref> designed exclusively for Harris Scarfe. The collection is known for original and whimsical designs.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category|position=left}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1849]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Advert|date=September 2019}}\n{{COI|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Harris Scarfe\n| logo                = HarrisScarfe.svg\n| type                = Retail, eCommerce\n| fate                = [[Administration (law)|Receivers and Managers]] appointed\n| founded             = {{start date and age|1849}}\n| founders            = George Peter Harris and John C. Lanyon\n| location_city       = [[Richmond, Victoria|Richmond]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| location_country    = Australia\n| location            = <!--modifies \"Head Office\" entry-->\n| industry            = [[Retail]]\n| locations           = 45 stores (February 2020)\n| products            = Bed linen, homewares, kitchenware, manchester, electrical goods, kitchen appliances, women's and men's apparel, intimates, footwear and luggage\n| num_employees       = 1200 ({{as of|2020|04|lc=y}})\n| parent              = {{unbulleted list|Greenlit Brands (2014 - November 2019)|Allegro Funds (since November 2019)}}\n| homepage            = {{url|harrisscarfe.com.au}}\n}}\n'''Harris Scarfe''' is an Australian retailer that sells bed linen, kitchenware, homewares, electrical appliances and apparel. It is headquartered in Melbourne. It has a growing e-commerce retail presence in Australia and is considered a multi-channel department store retailer.\n\nFounded in 1849, Harris Scarfe currently operates 66 retail stores nationally in two formats including \"Harris Scarfe\" [[department stores]] and \"Harris Scarfe Home\" homewares and kitchenware stores.\n\nIn December 2019, Harris Scarfe entered into voluntary administration after 170 years in operation. {{as of|2020|1}}, 21 of its 65 stores are set to close.\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\nHarris Scarfe traces its history to 10 February 1849, when the founding partners, George Peter Harris and John C. Lanyon, arrived in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]] on the ship, \"Candahar\", to establish a hardware and [[ironmonger]]y business. Lanyon left the partnership on 22 February 1855 and returned to London, where he subsequently opened up a buying house for Geo. P Harris and other businesses in South Australia. Additional partners, George Scarfe and Richard Smith, joined the business in 1866 and the business name \"Geo. P. Harris, Scarfe & Co.\" was adopted in December that year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207681585 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Adelaide Express]] |volume=IV |issue=914 |location=South Australia |date=17 December 1866 |accessdate=22 October 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nHarris Scarfe grew to become a major supplier of a broad range of household, agricultural and industrial items.  Besides conducting its retailing businesses, Harris Scarfe manufactured leather goods, including saddlery and luggage, as part of a wholesaling operation. Notably, during [[World War II]], when the [[Australian Government]] enforced price controls, it used the Harris Scarfe catalogue as the price guide.\n\n===1970s - 1980s===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2019}}\nIn 1971, Baradeen Quest Pty Limited, a subsidiary of Investment and Merchant Finance Corporation Limited (\"IMFC\") made a successful takeover bid for Harris Scarfe Limited, which was listed on the [[Australian Stock Exchange]] at the time.\n\n[[Charles Davis Limited]], a listed [[Tasmania]]n company controlled by [[Sir Donald Trescowthick]], acquired control of Harris Scarfe in 1976. Trescowthick focussed Harris Scarfe's activities on its retailing business, developing a full line department store model, while the industrial products outlet at [[Mile End, South Australia|Mile End]] evolved to become Harry's, a large hardware retailing business.\n\nThe success of Harry's led Harris Scarfe's parent company, Charles Davis Limited, to acquire other hardware retailers, including Lloyd's in South Australia, [[Campbell's]] in Queensland, and [[Bunnings Warehouse|McEwans]] in Victoria and New South Wales. In 1989, these hardware businesses were sold in a management buyout, and acquired by [[Bunnings]] in 1993.\n\n===1990s===\nIn the 1990s, Harris Scarfe entered an era of unprecedented national growth. It expanded beyond its large department store in Rundle Mall into smaller format suburban and regional shopping stores. Harris Scarfe also acquired full-line department store sites from other retailers who were rationalising their store networks including [[David Jones Limited|David Jones]], [[Myer]], John Martins, Stirling and Centre Fair. By 1995, Harris Scarfe had become Australia's third largest department store retailer, with 38 stores, and trading in all states of Australia.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe company ran into trouble during the late 1990s due to rising debts and management issues.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} In April 2001, the business was placed in receivership. Unsecured creditors were owed $93 million, and the company was $50 million in debt.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/former-harris-scarfe-executive-jailed-six-years-20020627-gduc7w.html|title=Former Harris Scarfe executive jailed six years|date=27 June 2002|work=[[The Age]]|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|agency=[[Australian Associated Press]]}}</ref> In June 2002, the company's former chief financial officer, Alan Hodgson, was sentenced to six years in jail, on multiple counts that included giving false information to the [[Australian Securities Exchange|ASX]], and failing to act honestly as a company officer.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2001, Harris Scarfe listed on the [[Australian Securities Exchange]] (ASX). In the same year, the company fell $160 million into debt, resulting in the owners, the Trescowthick family, losing $31.5 million. The government initially considered pressing charges against chairman Adam Trescowthick, but later dropped the case.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2002, the company started a revitalisation program. The store network was remodelled with new products, layouts and new branding. As a result, Harris Scarfe soon began to enjoy record growth. By 2007, Sydney-based Momentum Private Equity acquired an $80&nbsp;million majority stake in the company. During 2012, Momentum Corporate ten sold the business to [[Pepkor]], a South African private equity firm.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOver a six-month period at the end of 2003, Harris Scarfe made certain representations on a number of items in its catalogues in relation to pricing. Harris Scarfe admitted to the Australian Competition and Consumer Commission (ACCC) that representations in its promotional advertising may have misled consumers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accc.gov.au/media-release/harris-scarfe-admits-sale-prices-may-have-misled-issues-public-apology|title=Harris Scarfe admits sale prices may have misled, issues public apology|last=Commission|first=Australian Competition and Consumer|date=2013-02-23|website=Australian Competition and Consumer Commission|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nAgain in 2007 Harris Scarfe was investigated by the Australian consumer watchdog who sued the department store in the Australian Federal Court over allegedly false promotions for its sales in October 2006. The ACCC alleged that the advertising was misleading because Harris Scarfe was not offering what it advertised:\n\n# A discount off all goods in its stores.\n# A minimum of 20% off all goods in its stores.\n\nThe ACCC also alleged that the catalogue included images of products under banners stating a specific discount when some of those goods were not discounted by the stated percentage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcompany.com.au/marketing/advertising/accc-challenges-harris-scarfe-ads/|title=ACCC challenges Harris Scarfe ads|date=2007-10-12|website=SmartCompany|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the Federal Court, Adelaide has declared that Harris Scarfe Australia Pty Ltd misled consumers by representing in a catalogue that certain advertised items were discounted by a specific amount when in fact they were discounted by less than that amount, or were not discounted at all.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accc.gov.au/media-release/court-declares-harris-scarfe-misled-consumers|title=Court declares Harris Scarfe misled consumers|last=Commission|first=Australian Competition and Consumer|date=2013-02-23|website=Australian Competition and Consumer Commission|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHarris Scarfe CEO Robert Atkins, resigned from the top post at Harris Scarfe in March 2009 after eight years leading the turnaround of department store.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/exharris-scarfe-boss-robert-atkins-dies-20100115-mb6b.html|title=Ex-Harris Scarfe boss Robert Atkins dies|date=2010-01-15|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> He played a significant role in the restructuring of retail trading hours in South Australia and in the revitalisation of the state\u2019s premium retail precinct as chairman of the Rundle Mall Management Authority.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.retailbiz.com.au/offline-retailing/former-harris-scarfe-ceo-robert-atkins-dies/|title=Former Harris Scarfe CEO Robert Atkins dies|last=retailbizc0rD8|date=2010-01-15|website=retailbiz|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Robert Atkins passed away in January 2010.\n\nAfter Robert Atkins successful tenure leading Harris Scarfe, Joe Barberis was named managing director of the retailer in February 2009 until September 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.linkedin.com/in/joe-barberis-b3a2b96|title=Joe Barberis LinkedIn|last=Barberis|first=Joe|date=11 April 2020|website=LinkedIn|url-status=live}}</ref> Graham Dean, previously Myer group general manager of Electrical was named CEO of Harris Scarfe.\n\nIn 2012, Kyly Clarke became the face of Harris Scarfe's fashion home brand 'Boutique@hs'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.popsugar.com.au/fashion/Kyly-Clarke-Face-New-Harris-Scarfe-Fashion-Label-Boutiquehs-25432051|title=Kyly Clarke Is The Face of New Label Boutique@hs!|last=Rota|first=Genevieve|date=2012-10-14|website=POPSUGAR Fashion Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, Greenlit Brands, formerly [[Steinhoff International|Steinhoff Asia Pacific]], acquired [[Pepkor]] and this included Harris Scarfe. Harris Scarfe has been owned by Greenlit Brands since this time.<ref>https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/25/steinhoff-international-to-buy-pepkor-of-south-africa-for-5-7-billion/</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, General Manager of Harris Scarfe Daniel Nikoleaff was demoted to Area Manager of South Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.linkedin.com/in/daniel-nikoleaff-29325842|title=Daniel Nikoleaff - LinkedIn|last=Nikoleaff|first=Daniel|date=April 2020|website=LinkedIn|url-status=live}}</ref> Nikoleaff was replaced by Rebecca Peterson previously CEO of Lovisa jewellery stores.\n\nIn October 2013, Harris Scarfe officially launched Simply Vera,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.harrisscarfe.com.au/hs/Brands/Simply-Vera-Vera-Wang/SVVW | title=Simply Vera Vera Wang | accessdate=2020-03-03 }}</ref> by Vera Wang which is designed by [[Vera Wang]] who is based in [[New York City]]. The collection comprises a range of contemporary women's fashion, accessories, bed and bath collections and home fragrances.\n\nHarris Scarfe's home brand 'Bulls Head' Jeans were found to have harmful Azo dyes, which expert authorities classify as carcinogens. The Jeans were recalled in July 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.productsafety.gov.au/recall/harris-scarfe-pty-ltd-bulls-head-men-s-black-regular-short-leg-jeans|title=Harris Scarfe Pty Ltd\u2014Bulls Head Men\u2019s Black Regular & Short Leg Jeans|last=Australia|first=Product Safety|date=2016-07-28|website=Product Safety Australia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Harris Scarfe also collaborated with [[Shayna Blaze]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.harrisscarfe.com.au/hs/Brands/Shaynna-Blaze/SHYB | title=Shayna Blaze | accessdate=2020-03-03 }}</ref> an interior designer from [[The Block (Australian TV series)|The Block]] on bed linens, homewares, accessories and apparel.\n\nIn October 2017,  just before the Steinhoff corruption scandal unfolded, Steinhoff International appointed former The Good Guys boss Michael Ford, to oversee its Australasian operation. He had left behind a retailer that had to be significantly restructured due to cash flow problems and a lack of stock in the business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnews.com.au/insight-harris-scarfe-liquidation-dodgy-deal-or-acceptable-stitch-up-by-allegro-funds-suppliers-angry/|title=INSIGHT: Harris Scarfe Liquidation, \u2018Dodgy Deal\u2019 Or Acceptable \u2018Stitch Up\u2019 By Allegro Funds, Suppliers Angry \u2013 channelnews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\nBritish Fashion brand Debenhams granted exclusivity to Harris Scarfe for their launch in Australia in February 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hub.harrisscarfe.com.au/fashion/big-british-brands-from-debenhams-exclusive-to-us/|title=Big British Brands From Debenhams, Exclusive To Us.|date=2017-02-09|website=Harris Scarfe|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The arrangement was short lived and Harris Scarfe parted ways with Debenhams in November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/best-and-less-harris-scarfe-back-in-australian-hands-20191118-p53bp2.html|title=Best & Less, Harris Scarfe back in Australian hands|last=Powell|first=Dominic|date=2019-11-19|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nDuring April 2018, they launched a new collection with [[Jamie Durie]], TV personality [[The Outdoor Room]] named Jamie Durie by Ardor<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.harrisscarfe.com.au/hs/Brands/JAMIE-DURIE/JDUR | title=Jamie Durie | accessdate=2020-03-03 }}</ref> which is a casual bed linen product range.\n\nChannel Seven Morning Show presenter Kylie Gillies was named Harris Scarfe's fashion ambassador in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hub.harrisscarfe.com.au/whats-new/our-newest-fashion-ambassador/|title=Our newest fashion ambassador|date=2018-08-07|website=Harris Scarfe|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, parent company Greenlit Brands sold both Harris Scarfe and [[Best & Less]] to Australian private equity firm Allegro Funds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/best-and-less-harris-scarfe-back-in-australian-hands-20191118-p53bp2.html|title=Best & Less, Harris Scarfe back in Australian hands|last=Powell|first=Dominic|date=19 November 2019|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insideretail.com.au/news/greenlit-brands-offloads-best-less-harris-scarfe-and-debenhams-201911|title=Greenlit Brands offloads Best & Less, Harris Scarfe and Debenhams|last=McIlvaine|first=Heather|date=19 November 2019|work=Inside Retail|access-date=21 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/retail/greenlit-brands-harris-scarfe-best-and-less-sold-to-allegro-20191118-p53bgk|title=Greenlit Brands' Harris Scarfe, Best & Less sold to Allegro|last=Mitchell|first=Sue|date=18 November 2019|work=[[Australian Financial Review]]|access-date=11 December 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 - 2020: Voluntary administration, Trading Insolvent and Supplier Scandal  ===\nOn 11 December 2019, Harris Scarfe under General Manager Rebecca Peterson,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.linkedin.com/in/rebecca-peterson-88389255|title=LinkedIn Profile|last=Peterson|first=Rebecca|date=2 April 2020|website=LinkedIn|url-status=live}}</ref> entered voluntary administration, with Deloitte Restructuring Services partners taking over management of the business. The retailer reported $380 million in annual sales earlier in the year. At the time, Harris Scarfe had 66 stores employing 1800 staff.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/harris-scarfe-collapses-into-voluntary-administration-66-stores-in-jeopardy/6af1f6ab-f81e-4a8b-a8ec-c3f124c44e43|title=Aussie retailer Harris Scarfe collapses after 170 years in business|last=Marsh|first=Stuart|date=11 December 2019|work=[[Nine News]]|access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/harris-scarfe-department-chain-in-receivership-in-horror-year-for-retailers-20191211-p53iy8.html|title=Harris Scarfe department chain enters receivership in horror year for retailers|last=Cummins|first=Carolyn|date=11 December 2019|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref> In response, the [[Shop, Distributive and Allied Employees Association]] labour union said that they would be filing a complaint with the [[Fair Work Commission]] because they were not informed in advance. Deloitte claims Harris Scarfe has \"more than sufficient\" assets to pay all staff entitlements.<ref name=\":0\" /> In January 2020, Harris Scarfe announced it would close 21 of its 65 stores, resulting in the loss of 440 jobs. 1380 staff would remain in the 44 stores still in operation.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.insideretail.com.au/news/harris-scarfe-closing-21-stores-202001|title=Harris Scarfe closing 21 stores|last=Blake|first=Dean|date=6 January 2020|work=Inside Retail|access-date=21 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The closures consist of one in [[South Australia]] and in the [[Australian Capital Territory]], two in [[Western Australia]], three in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], six in [[Queensland]], and eight in [[New South Wales]], all due to close within four weeks.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/retail/440-jobs-21-stores-to-go-at-harris-scarfe-20200106-p53pan|title=440 jobs, 21 stores to go at Harris Scarfe|last=Baird|first=Lucas|date=6 January 2020|work=[[Australian Financial Review]]|access-date=21 January 2020|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> As of 2 February 2020, 20 stores have closed, with the store in Earlville, Cairns, being spared from closure, leaving 45 stores, being 3 in Australian Capital Territory, 3 in Queensland, 5 in Tasmania, 5 in New South Wales, 8 in South Australia and 21 in Victoria.\n\nDuring this time Harris Scarfe's credit card services and interest free offers were no longer honoured or available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cards.harrisscarfe.com.au/harris-scarfe-value-plus-card-currently-unavailable/|title=Harris Scarfe Value Plus Card: Currently Unavailable \u2013 Harris Scarfe Value Plus Credit Cards|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March 2020, it was announced that fabric and home fitting store [[Spotlight]] will purchase the remaining stores.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/spotlight-set-to-save-harris-scarfe-from-collapse-20200303-p546bm.html | title=Spotlight set to save Harris Scarfe from collapse | work=The Sydney Morning Herald| first=Dominic | last=Powell | date=2020-03-03 | accessdate=2020-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://indaily.com.au/news/business/2020/03/03/spotlight-wins-right-to-buy-harris-scarfe/ | title=Spotlight wins right to buy Harris Scarfe | work=InDaily | first=Bension | last=Siebert | date=2020-03-03 | accessdate=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2020 Harris Scarfe layed off a further 59 staff. Announced the day after Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison announced the national JobKeeper Scheme. Deloitte, which acted as Harris Scarfe\u2019s receiver, expects the sale to be finalised just after Easter. Staff were initially told the redundancies were being made due to the current economic conditions and COVID-19 crisis. This was later backtracked to claim the redundancies were part of the sale process. And that, while Harris Scarfe will be applying for the Government\u2019s JobKeeper initiative to support remaining staff, those let go on 'restructuring' grounds may not be supported under the payment scheme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideretail.com.au/news/harris-scarfe-lays-off-59-staff-offers-referrals-to-centrelink-202004|title=Harris Scarfe lays off 59 staff, offers referrals to Centrelink|date=2020-04-01|website=Inside Retail|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2020, Smart Company reported Harris Scarfe were being investigated by the retail Union for possibly breaching the Fair Work Act and treating their staff unfairly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcompany.com.au/industries/retail/harris-scarfe-workers-redundancy/|title=Harris Scarfe workers outraged as receivers make 59 staff redundant the day after wage subsidy announcement|date=2020-04-03|website=SmartCompany|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nThe Mercury newspaper in Tasmania reported on 7 April 2020, Harris Scarfe's newly renovated Hobart store would be closing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themercury.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TMWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.themercury.com.au%2Fnews%2Ftasmania%2Fharris-scarfes-hobart-store-will-close-its-doors-in-the-near-future%2Fnews-story%2Fb7e3d36a22ebcff571f34e977eb0929a&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=bc6fff70f9d21ef3a83df3c1de171760-1586612184|title=Subscribe to The Mercury|website=www.themercury.com.au|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntnews.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=NTWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ntnews.com.au%2Fnews%2Fharris-scarfes-hobart-store-will-close-its-doors-in-the-near-future%2Fnews-story%2Fb7e3d36a22ebcff571f34e977eb0929a&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=5cc4bb36e468ae699f905582f05b7ca3-1586612247|title=Subscribe to the NT News|website=www.ntnews.com.au|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Australian financial review reported on 8 April 2020 that Harris Scarfe was still in the red despite Spotlight deal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/retail/harris-scarfe-creditors-in-the-red-despite-spotlight-deal-20200408-p54i9b|title=Harris Scarfe creditors in the red despite Spotlight deal|date=2020-04-08|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> On 9 April 2020 Channel News added \"Several appliance and CE distributors are set to only get between 1.3\u00a2 and 20.5\u00a2 in the dollar under a proposed deed of company arrangement for the failed Harris Scarfe, Allegro the Company who owned the stores for only three weeks will get $70M...The Australian Financial Review reported that the receivers blamed Harris Scarfe\u2019s collapse on loss-making stores, most of which opened between 2014 and 2019, and the retailer\u2019s inability to access funding after the sale to Allegro, which is the first ranking secured creditor and will receive a return of almost $70 million.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnews.com.au/harris-scarfe-ce-appliance-suppliers-set-to-only-get-cents-but-5-week-owner-gets-70m/|title=Harris Scarfe CE & Appliance Suppliers Set To Only Get Cents But 5 Week Owner Gets $70M \u2013 channelnews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24th 2020, The Herald Sun reported Harris Scarfe became insolvent the moment private equity firm Allegro Funds took control of the struggling department store chain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=HSWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.heraldsun.com.au%2Fbusiness%2Fharris-scarfe-claim-insolvent-from-the-word-go%2Fnews-story%2F55e2a428728d413890655dfd8bccf7d3&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=e9fb864dbad35e955f5d8702972638da-1588158889|title=Heraldsun.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to the Herald Sun for exclusive stories|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> Days later Channel News had spoken to unhappy suppliers who were allegedly ripped off and believe the company's collapse was an orchestrated con.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnews.com.au/insight-harris-scarfe-liquidation-dodgy-deal-or-acceptable-stitch-up-by-allegro-funds-suppliers-angry/|title=INSIGHT: Harris Scarfe Liquidation, \u2018Dodgy Deal\u2019 Or Acceptable \u2018Stitch Up\u2019 By Allegro Funds, Suppliers Angry \u2013 channelnews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> Channel News in a follow up reported Harris Scarfe had illegally traded insolvent during December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnews.com.au/ripped-off-insolvent-harris-scarfe-allegro-funds-deal-looks-like-another-dick-smith-anchorage-capital-saga/|title=\u201cRipped Off\u201d Insolvent Harris Scarfe Allegro Funds Deal, Looks Like Another Dick Smith Anchorage Capital Saga \u2013 channelnews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> \n\nCommercial Real Estate reported on April 28th 2020 that Harris Scarfe's new owner Spotlight refused to pay its monthly rent for all stores. They were unwilling to work with landlords, demanding a 50% reduction on all rent. Spotlight also had yet to pay $50 million for the newly acquired Harris Scarfe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commercialrealestate.com.au/news/spotlight-halts-april-rent-demands-50pc-cut-951705/|title=Spotlight halts April rent, demands 50pc cut|last=Schlesinger|first=Larry|date=2020-04-28|website=Commercial Real Estate|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> \n\nAs of April 2020, approximately 1200 staff remain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcompany.com.au/industries/retail/harris-scarfe-workers-redundancy/|title=Harris Scarfe workers outraged as receivers make 59 staff redundant the day after wage subsidy announcement|date=2020-04-03|website=SmartCompany|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Store formats==\n'''Harris Scarfe department stores''' sell a full range of bed linen, homewares, cookware, manchester, apparel, electrical appliances, kitchen appliances, menswear, womenswear, intimates, sportswear, travel and outdoor. There are currently 40 Harris Scarfe stores.\n\n'''Harris Scarfe Home''' stores sell homewares including bed linen, homewares, cookware, kitchen appliances, electrical goods, personal care and bathroom electrical. There are currently five Harris Scarfe Home stores.\n\n== Product categories ==\nHarris Scarfe stores sell the following products:\n* Bed Linen & Manchester \u2013 bedding, linen, towels, manchester, pillows, decorative cushions\n* Homewares \u2013 crockery, cutlery, glassware, food preparation\n* Kitchenware and Cookware  \u2013 cook sets, fry pans, cast iron \n* Personal Care & Bathroom Electrical \u2013 hairdryers, shavers\n* Kitchen Appliances \u2013 kettles, toasters, food processors, blenders\n* Electrical Appliances - heaters, fans, cookers, grills, toasters \n* Clothing and Apparel - womenswear, menswear\n* Travel \u2013 luggage, accessories\n\n==Exclusive brands==\n\n=== Smith + Nobel ===\nSmith + Nobel is Harris Scarfe's budget home brand. The Smith + Nobel name is used across Manchester, Homewares and Electrical. A majority of Harris Scarfe's stock is under the Smith + Nobel name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harrisscarfe.com.au/search?text=smith+and+nobel|title=Search smith and nobel {{!}} HS Site|website=www.harrisscarfe.com.au|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Simply Vera \u2013 Vera Wang ===\nIn October 2013, Harris Scarfe were officially launched<ref>{{cite web |url = http://graciousmagazine.blogspot.com.au/2013/09/simply-vera-vera-wang-for-harris-scarfe.html |title = Simply Vera \u2013 Vera Wang for Harris Scarfe |date = 25 September 2013 |author= Sweaty Betty PR |publisher = Gracious Magazine}}</ref> as the only Australian retailer allowed to sell the Simply Vera range<ref>{{cite web |url = http://fashioninitiative.com.au/fashion/simply-vera-vera-wang-sold-collaborates-with-heritage-department-store-harris-scarfe/ |title = Simply Vera \u2013 Vera Wang collaborates with heritage department store Harris Scarfe. |date = 22 October 2013 |first = Phoebes |last = Garland  |publisher = fashioninitiative.com.au }}</ref> designed by [[Vera Wang]] who is based in [[New York City]]. The collection comprises a range of contemporary women's fashion, accessories, bed and bath collections & home fragrance.\n\n=== Shayna Blaze ===\nShayna Blaze homewares collection<ref>{{cite web |url = http://fortemag.com.au/?p=34955 |title = Shayna Blaze for Harris Scarfe |date = 18 October 2017 |author= Forte Magazine |publisher = Forte Magazine }}</ref> designed by [[Shayna Blaze]].  The collection includes bed linen, homewares and apparel.\n\n=== Jamie Durie - By Ardor ===\nJamie Durie homewares collection<ref>{{cite web |url = https://hub.harrisscarfe.com.au/home/the-art-of-bringing-the-outdoors-in-with-jamie-durie-by-ardor/ |title = The Art of bringing the outdoors in with Jamie Durie by Ardor |date = 16 April 2018 |author= Harris Scarfe |publisher = hub Harris Scarfe }}</ref> designed by [[Jamie Durie]].  The collection includes casual bed linens, cushions and sheet sets that are designed to bring nature inside the home.\n\n=== MOZI ===\nMOZI is a Melbourne-based lifestyle brand specialising in unique Australian designed homewares, lifestyle and bath & body products.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.houzz.com.au/professionals/furniture-and-accessories/mozi-australia-pfvwau-pf~1763424851 |title = MOZI Lifestyle Brand Exclusively at Harris Scarfe |date = 20 October 2018 |author= Houzz |publisher = hub Houzz }}</ref> designed exclusively for Harris Scarfe. The collection is known for original and whimsical designs.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category|position=left}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1849]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "V260z", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added quote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harris_Scarfe"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 pandemic in North Korea}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case = \n| location = [[North Korea]]\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| arrival_date =\n| image = \n| caption = \n| recovery_cases = \n| deaths =\n| confirmed_cases = 0\n| suspected_cases =\n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\n{{Politics of North Korea|width=22.0em}}\n\nThere are no officially confirmed cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[North Korea]], though foreign analysts believe that the virus has spread to the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3074377/coronavirus-nearly-200-north-korea-soldiers-die-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: nearly 200 North Korea soldiers 'die from outbreak government refuses to acknowledge'|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> The North Korean government has taken extensive measures, including quarantines and travel restrictions, which US analyst website [[38 North]] said appeared to be successful in containing the virus.<ref name=38north-20200423/>\n\n==Background==\nNorth Korea is an impoverished country with a [[Healthcare in North Korea|weak healthcare system]] and [[Sanctions against North Korea|is subject to sanctions]], rendering it vulnerable in the event of an outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Korea says detected North Korea missile fire 'inapproriate' amid coronavirus |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/north-korea-fired-suspected-short-range-missiles-south-korea-says.html |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> There is concern that widespread malnutrition could exacerbate the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> North Korean public health official Pak Myong-su said that if the disease spread in North Korea, \"a serious disaster could not be avoided\".<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\"/>\n\nDiplomatically and economically isolated,<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> the country borders China, the starting point of the pandemic, which is North Korea's closest ally, most important trading partner, and a source of tourists.<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/><ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\">{{cite news |last1=Sang-Hun |first1=Choe |title=North Korea Claims No Coronavirus Cases. Can It Be Trusted? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/world/asia/north-korea-coronavirus.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korea's government is secretive and the media are tightly controlled, making it hard for outside observers to determine what is really going on in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\nHistorically, North Korea has restricted travel in the face of epidemics abroad, for instance during the [[2014 Ebola epidemic]].<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> Moreover, the country has had success in disease eradication in the past; it reportedly eliminated [[measles]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Minal K. |title=Progress Toward Regional Measles Elimination \u2014 Worldwide, 2000\u20132018 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/68/wr/mm6848a1.htm |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |date=2019 |language=en-us |doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm6848a1}}</ref><ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> [[Government of North Korea|North Korea's government]] is highly [[totalitarian]] and maintains strict control over the country and its society, which experts anticipated could help in enforcing disease control measures such as [[social distancing]].<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/><ref name=\"NK News - North Korea News\">{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> North Korea also has a large number of doctors, though they are less skilled and equipped than their Western counterparts, and a high level of public hygiene.<ref name=\"NK News - North Korea News\"/>\n\nSome South Korean sources state that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the pandemic]] is steadily affecting the country. The virus is more likely to have come into North Korea from [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]], where the virus originated, than from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]]. The [[China\u2013North Korea border|Chinese-North Korean border]] restrictions are more relaxed than the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone|heavily militarized border]] between North and South Korea. However, suspected COVID-19 cases in the two Chinese provinces ([[Liaoning]] and [[Jilin]]) bordering North Korea have been low.<ref name=\"Who Knows\">{{Cite web |title=Who Knows How Many Virus Cases North Korea Has. It Says Zero |last1=Wainer |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Jihye |work=Bloomberg.com |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/north-korea-s-official-virus-tally-zero-experts-aren-t-so-sure }}</ref>\n\nNorth Korea prevented the entry of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] in 2003 and [[Ebola]] in 2014.<ref name=38north-20200220>{{cite news |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/02/eimaabrahamian022020/ |title=Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way |first1=Esther S. |last1=Im |first2=Andray |last2=Abrahamian |publisher=The Henry L. Stimson Center |work=38 North |date=20 February 2020 |access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\n[[File:Masikryong-Hotel-and-Lift.jpg|200px|thumb|left|[[Masikryong Ski Resort]], a popular ski resort in North Korea. Due to the outbreak of the virus, ski resorts and spas in North Korea have been closed.]]\n\nNorth Korea was one of the first countries to close borders due to COVID-19.<ref name=38north-20200220/> The government has implemented widespread travel restrictions,<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\">{{cite news |last1=Shinkman |first1=Paul D. |title=North Korea Opens Borders to Aid Amid Coronavirus Threat |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-13/north-korea-opens-borders-to-aid-amid-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> including closing the border to foreign tourists in late January 2020<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\">{{cite news |title=North Korea Bars Foreign Tourists Amid Virus Threat, Groups Say |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/north-korea-bars-foreign-tourists-amid-virus-threat-groups-say |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=22 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and then suspending flights and banning travel in and out of the country.<ref name=38north-20200220/> Though many parts of the border were closed, the bridge between [[Dandong]] and [[Sinuiju]] remained open and allowed supplies to be delivered.<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\">{{cite news |title=Russia Delivers Coronavirus Test Kits to North Korea |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-12/russia-delivers-coronavirus-test-kits-to-north-korea |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In late February, the North Korean government said that it would keep the border closed until a cure was found.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nThe possibility of a COVID-19 outbreak in North Korea is a concern to international organizations and observers due to the country's poverty and low-quality healthcare infrastructure. Outside organizations have provided aid to help the country fight the virus: the Russian government provided [[COVID-19 testing|test kits]],<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> the [[World Health Organization]] announced plans to send supplies despite the lack of confirmed cases, and the [[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies]], [[U.S. State Department]], and South Korean government all indicated willingness to help.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> The U.S. government worked with the United Nations to make exceptions to sanctions, though they were also criticized for slowing down the process for providing aid.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/> [[Doctors Without Borders]] said in late March that supplies of diagnostic equipment and [[personal protective equipment]] were stranded on the Chinese border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early February, the [[North Korean government]] took severe measures to block the spread of the coronavirus. ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'', the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] newspaper, reported that the customs officials at [[Nampho]] port were performing disinfection activities, including placing imported goods in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kcnawatch.org/newstream/1583703072-617647256/\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744-\uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c-\ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4-\uc5c6\uac8c/ |script-title=ko:\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744 \uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c \ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4 \uc5c6\uac8c |language=ko |date=2020-03-09 |accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref> All international flights and railway services were suspended in early February, and connections by sea and road were largely closed over the following weeks.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nIn February, wearing face masks was obligatory and visiting public places such as restaurants was forbidden. Ski resorts and spas were closed and military parades, marathons, and other public events were cancelled.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nSchools were closed throughout the country; university students in Pyongyang from elsewhere in the country were confined to their dormitories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=Sources: N. Korea extends school closures until April 15 |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-north-korea-extends-school-closures-until-april-15/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\">{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=N. Korea closes schools throughout the country for one month |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-closes-schools-throughout-country-one-month/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean citizens returning from other countries were subjected to a 40-day isolation period to which was added a 30-day \"medical observation\" period. According to North Korean media, nearly 7,000 North Koreans were subjected to these rules on 1 March.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nAccording to the North Korean government, 10,000 people had been quarantined by the end of March.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/> From 12 February, the 14-day quarantine on all foreigners (including their local staff) was extended to 30 days.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Diplomats and other foreigners were evacuated to [[Vladivostok]] in March.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/><ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> By 27 March, according to North Korean media, there were only two foreigners in quarantine and 2,280 North Koreans were under \"medical observation\" in areas such as [[South Phyongan]] province and [[North Phyongan]] province, [[Ryanggang]] province, and the city of [[Rason]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe North Korean military fired five missiles on two occasions in early March 2020, which may be \"an effort to ensure the country remains on the agenda for other nations amid the virus outbreak\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> More missile tests followed in late March, along with an announcement that the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] would meet in early April. Foreign observers said the government was trying to show confidence in their handling of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Missile tests and meetings: North Korea signals confidence in face of coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea-analysi/missile-tests-and-meetings-north-korea-signals-confidence-in-face-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN21A0O7 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The South Korean military called the provocation \"extremely inappropriate\" in light of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea Fires Missile Into East Sea |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-28/north-korea-fires-missile-into-east-sea-s-korea-military-says |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals.<ref name=\"Fox News\">{{Cite news| url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/kim-jong-un-north-korea-hospital-coronavirus |title = Kim Jong Un orders workers to build new hospitals as North Korea continues to claim no coronavirus cases |work=[[Fox News]] |date = 2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nKim Jong-un sent a letter to South Korean president [[Moon Jae-in]] as a show of support amidst the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|outbreak in South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Top U.S. Commander 'Fairly Certain' North Korea Has Virus Cases |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-14/top-u-s-commander-fairly-certain-north-korea-has-virus-cases |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=14 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] wrote a letter to [[Kim Jong-un]] to express his willingness to work with him on dealing with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea says Trump wrote Kim, offered coronavirus cooperation |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-northkorea-idUSKBN2180YX |work=Reuters |date=2020-03-21}}</ref> North Korean state media has reported on the severity of the outbreak in other countries.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/>\n\nOn 31 March 2020, the ''[[Asia Times]]'' reported that North Korea's measures against the pandemic seemed largely successful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/north-koreas-silent-struggle-against-covid-19/|title=North Korea's silent struggle against Covid-19|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Edwin Salvador, WHO's representative in North Korea, reported that as of 2 April, 709 people had been tested, with no confirmed cases, and 509 people were in quarantine.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea/north-korea-testing-quarantining-for-covid-19-still-says-no-cases-who-representative-idUSKBN21P3C2|title=North Korea testing, quarantining for COVID-19, still says no cases: WHO representative|first=Stephanie|last=Nebehay|publisher=Reuters|date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, Kim Jong-un presided over a meeting of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]. The meeting adopted a joint resolution by the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]], [[State Affairs Commission of North Korea|State Affairs Commission]] and the [[Cabinet of North Korea|Cabinet]], \"On more thoroughly taking national measures for protecting the life and safety of our people from the worldwide epidemic disease\". The resolution called to take strict national countermeasures to thoroughly check the inroads of the virus due to the steady spread of the epidemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/04/kim-jong-un-guides-saturdays-politburo-meeting-ahead-of-spa-state-media/|title=North Korea's Politburo discusses \"danger\" from COVID-19, promotes officials|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, US analyst website [[38 North]] reported that North Korea's early and extensive response appeared to be successful in containing the virus.<ref name=38north-20200423/>\n\n==Impact==\nAlthough South Korean media shared news hinting at the spread of the COVID-19 epidemic to North Korea, the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] denied the veracity of such claims. On 18 February, ''Rodong Sinmun'' quoted a public health official reiterating the country had had \"no confirmed case of the new coronavirus so far\". The WHO prioritised aid for North Korea, including the shipment of protective equipment and supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|title=World Health Organization says there are 'no indications' of coronavirus cases in North Korea|publisher=CNBC|date=19 February 2020|access-date=19 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219100113/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Military===\nIn early March, the North Korean government continued to deny that they had any cases of [[COVID-19]]. However, according to [[South Korea]]n media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'', 180 soldiers had died. There was no estimate of those merely infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3074377/coronavirus-nearly-200-north-korea-soldiers-die-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: nearly 200 North Korea soldiers 'die from outbreak government refuses to acknowledge'|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February and March, U.S. officials observed a decrease in military activity in North Korea, believed to be a sign that there are COVID-19 cases in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> General [[Robert B. Abrams]] observed that the North Korean military had \"been on lockdown for about 30 days\" and \"didn\u2019t fly an airplane for 24 days\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\n===Political===\nThe underground network that assists [[North Korean defectors|defectors in escaping North Korea]] has been almost unable to operate amidst strict controls implemented to stop the virus, with defection attempts being suspended.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\">{{cite news |title=Group of North Korean women and children escape coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.ft.com/content/253d5ff0-63e9-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.ft.com |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Defection rates had been declining already, probably due to increased security under the administrations of [[Kim Jong-un]] in North Korea and [[Xi Jinping]] in China.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\"/>\n\n===Economic===\nOn 26 March, the New York Times reported satellite imagery shared by the [[Royal United Services Institute]], which showed that the illicit trafficking of coal and other goods stopped, with the commercial vessels now idling in their home ports.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/video/coronavirus-north-korea.html</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===January 2020===\nFrom 23 January, North Korea banned [[Tourism in North Korea|foreign tourists]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/north-korea-to-temporarily-ban-tourists-over-wuhan-virus-fears-says-tour-company|title=North Korea to temporarily ban tourists over Wuhan virus fears, says tour company|last=hermesauto|date=21 January 2020|website=The Straits Times|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, suspected cases in [[Sinuiju]] were quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|title=N. Korea quarantines suspected coronavirus cases in Sinuiju|website=Daily NK|date=28 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130223216/https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, North Korea's news agency [[KCNA]] declared a \"state emergency\" and reported the establishment of anti-epidemic headquarters around the country.<ref name=\"20200206cnn\">{{cite news |last1=Berlinger |first1=Joshua |last2=Seo |first2=Yoonjung |title=All of its neighbors have it, so why hasn't North Korea reported any coronavirus cases? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207093221/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html |archive-date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=7 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 2 February, KCNA reported that all the people who had entered the country after 13 January were placed under \"medical supervision\".<ref name=\"20200206cnn\"/>\n\nOn 7 February, South Korean media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'' claimed that five North Koreans in [[Sinuiju]] on the Chinese border died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|title=Sources: Five N. Koreans died from coronavirus infections|author=Jang Seul Gi|website=Daily NK|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082046/https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Within the same day, ''[[The Korea Times]]'' reported that a North Korean female living in the capital [[Pyongyang]] was infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|title=Coronavirus spreads to North Korea, woman infected|website=The Standard|location=Hong Kong|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082206/https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite no confirmation by North Korean authorities on the claims, the country has implemented stricter measures to combat the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pyongyangtimes.com.kp/?bbs=33091|title=Nation steps up fight against novel CoV|website=The Pyongyang Times|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rodong.rep.kp/en/index.php?strPageID=SF01_02_01&newsID=2020-02-08-0001|title=Work to Curb the Inflow of Infectious Disease Pushed ahead with|website=Rodong Sinmun|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed starting on 20 February.<ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\"/>\n\nOn 29 February, [[Kim Jong-un]] called for stronger measures to be taken to prevent COVID-19 from spreading to North Korea.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/kim-warns-consequences-virus-spreads-korea-200229061648473.html | title=Kim warns of 'serious consequences' if virus spreads to N Korea |work=al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 9 March 2020, the South Korean-based [[Daily NK]] reported an informant inside North Korea's military stating that 180 soldiers had died in January and February and about 3,700 soldiers were in quarantine.<ref name=dailynk-20200309>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-almost-200-soldiers-have-died-covid-19/ |title=Sources: Almost 200 soldiers have died from COVID-19 |author=Jeong Tae Joo |newspaper=Daily NK |date=9 March 2020 |access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2020, North Korea state media reported there were no confirmed cases in its territory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Stella |last2=Hagen |first2=Isobel |date=March 14, 2020 |title=North Korea claims it has no coronavirus cases |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/live-blog/coronavirus-updates-live-house-approves-coronavirus-aid-bill-n1158821/ncrd1158881#liveBlogHeader |work=NBC News |access-date=March 14, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals in North Korea. North Korean state media also reported that groundbreaking on a new hospital was underway the day prior on Tuesday 17 March. Kim Jong-un reportedly told a newspaper linked to the ruling [[Workers' Party of Korea]] that the construction of new hospitals were being done for general improvement of the nation's healthcare system without mentioning COVID-19.<ref name=\"Fox News\"/>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, North Korean media stated that more than 2,590 people had been released from quarantine in [[North Pyongan]] and [[South Pyongan]] provinces. All but three quarantined foreigners had been released.<ref name=\"aa.com.tr 21\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: North Korea releases quarantined people |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-north-korea-releases-quarantined-people/1773332 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April 2020, North Korean public health official Pak Myong-su repeated the claim that North Korea has no cases of the virus.<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\">{{cite news |title=N. Korea has no infected people with new coronavirus: expert |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200402/p2g/00m/0in/025000c |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Mainichi Daily News |date=2 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On 23 April 2020, it was reported that the country has taken 740 coronavirus tests, and all of them came back negative.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Norman |first1=Greg |title=North Korea claims 740 coronavirus tests came back negative, thousands released from quarantine |url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/north-korea-claims-740-coronavirus-tests-come-back-negative |website=Fox News |accessdate=24 April 2020 |date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2020, the [[Daily NK]] reported that a defecting North Korean who was shot attempting to cross the Tumen River into China tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korean-tests-positive-for-covid-19-china/|title=N. Korean tests positive for COVID-19 in China|last=Gi|first=Jang Seul|date=2020-04-23|website=Daily NK|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\nIn mid to late April restrictions on foreigners travelling in Pyongyang were relaxed, [[Nampo]] harbour was reopened to container ships, and the 14th [[Supreme People's Assembly]] of hundreds of delegates not wearing face masks was held.<ref name=38north-20200423>{{cite news |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/04/kparkjjongyjung042320/ |title=Do They or Do They Not Have COVID-19 Inside North Korea? |first1=Kee B. |last1=Park |first2=Jessup |last2=Jong |first3=Youngwoo |last3=Jung |publisher=The Henry L. Stimson Center |work=38 North |date=23 April 2020 |access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=38north-20200413>{{cite news |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/04/rfrank041320/ |title=The 2020 Parliamentary Session in North Korea: Self-Criticism and Dubious Optimism Concerning Economic Development |last=Frank |first=Ruediger |publisher=The Henry L. Stimson Center |work=38 North |date=13 April 2020 |access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Health in North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Medicine|North Korea|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 in North Korea|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in North Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 pandemic in North Korea}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case = \n| location = [[North Korea]]\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| arrival_date =\n| image = \n| caption = \n| recovery_cases = \n| deaths =\n| confirmed_cases = 0\n| suspected_cases =\n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\n{{Politics of North Korea|width=22.0em}}\n\nThere are no officially confirmed cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[North Korea]], though foreign analysts believe that the virus has spread to the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3074377/coronavirus-nearly-200-north-korea-soldiers-die-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: nearly 200 North Korea soldiers 'die from outbreak government refuses to acknowledge'|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> The North Korean government has taken extensive measures, including quarantines and travel restrictions, which US analyst website [[38 North]] said appeared to be successful in containing the virus.<ref name=38north-20200423/>\n\n==Background==\nNorth Korea is an impoverished country with a [[Healthcare in North Korea|weak healthcare system]] and [[Sanctions against North Korea|is subject to sanctions]], rendering it vulnerable in the event of an outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Korea says detected North Korea missile fire 'inapproriate' amid coronavirus |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/north-korea-fired-suspected-short-range-missiles-south-korea-says.html |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> There is concern that widespread malnutrition could exacerbate the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> North Korean public health official Pak Myong-su said that if the disease spread in North Korea, \"a serious disaster could not be avoided\".<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\"/>\n\nDiplomatically and economically isolated,<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> the country borders China, the starting point of the pandemic, which is North Korea's closest ally, most important trading partner, and a source of tourists.<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/><ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\">{{cite news |last1=Sang-Hun |first1=Choe |title=North Korea Claims No Coronavirus Cases. Can It Be Trusted? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/world/asia/north-korea-coronavirus.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korea's government is secretive and the media are tightly controlled, making it hard for outside observers to determine what is really going on in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\nHistorically, North Korea has restricted travel in the face of epidemics abroad, for instance during the [[2014 Ebola epidemic]].<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> Moreover, the country has had success in disease eradication in the past; it reportedly eliminated [[measles]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Minal K. |title=Progress Toward Regional Measles Elimination \u2014 Worldwide, 2000\u20132018 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/68/wr/mm6848a1.htm |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |date=2019 |language=en-us |doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm6848a1}}</ref><ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> [[Government of North Korea|North Korea's government]] is highly [[totalitarian]] and maintains strict control over the country and its society, which experts anticipated could help in enforcing disease control measures such as [[social distancing]].<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/><ref name=\"NK News - North Korea News\">{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> North Korea also has a large number of doctors, though they are less skilled and equipped than their Western counterparts, and a high level of public hygiene.<ref name=\"NK News - North Korea News\"/>\n\nSome South Korean sources state that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the pandemic]] is steadily affecting the country. The virus is more likely to have come into North Korea from [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]], where the virus originated, than from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]]. The [[China\u2013North Korea border|Chinese-North Korean border]] restrictions are more relaxed than the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone|heavily militarized border]] between North and South Korea. However, suspected COVID-19 cases in the two Chinese provinces ([[Liaoning]] and [[Jilin]]) bordering North Korea have been low.<ref name=\"Who Knows\">{{Cite web |title=Who Knows How Many Virus Cases North Korea Has. It Says Zero |last1=Wainer |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Jihye |work=Bloomberg.com |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/north-korea-s-official-virus-tally-zero-experts-aren-t-so-sure }}</ref>\n\nNorth Korea prevented the entry of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] in 2003 and [[Ebola]] in 2014.<ref name=38north-20200220>{{cite news |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/02/eimaabrahamian022020/ |title=Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way |first1=Esther S. |last1=Im |first2=Andray |last2=Abrahamian |publisher=The Henry L. Stimson Center |work=38 North |date=20 February 2020 |access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\n[[File:Masikryong-Hotel-and-Lift.jpg|200px|thumb|left|[[Masikryong Ski Resort]], a popular ski resort in North Korea. Due to the outbreak of the virus, ski resorts and spas in North Korea have been closed.]]\n\nNorth Korea was one of the first countries to close borders due to COVID-19.<ref name=38north-20200220/> The government has implemented widespread travel restrictions,<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\">{{cite news |last1=Shinkman |first1=Paul D. |title=North Korea Opens Borders to Aid Amid Coronavirus Threat |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-13/north-korea-opens-borders-to-aid-amid-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> including closing the border to foreign tourists in late January 2020<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\">{{cite news |title=North Korea Bars Foreign Tourists Amid Virus Threat, Groups Say |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/north-korea-bars-foreign-tourists-amid-virus-threat-groups-say |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=22 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and then suspending flights and banning travel in and out of the country.<ref name=38north-20200220/> Though many parts of the border were closed, the bridge between [[Dandong]] and [[Sinuiju]] remained open and allowed supplies to be delivered.<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\">{{cite news |title=Russia Delivers Coronavirus Test Kits to North Korea |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-12/russia-delivers-coronavirus-test-kits-to-north-korea |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In late February, the North Korean government said that it would keep the border closed until a cure was found.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nThe possibility of a COVID-19 outbreak in North Korea is a concern to international organizations and observers due to the country's poverty and low-quality healthcare infrastructure. Outside organizations have provided aid to help the country fight the virus: the Russian government provided [[COVID-19 testing|test kits]],<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> the [[World Health Organization]] announced plans to send supplies despite the lack of confirmed cases, and the [[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies]], [[U.S. State Department]], and South Korean government all indicated willingness to help.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> The U.S. government worked with the United Nations to make exceptions to sanctions, though they were also criticized for slowing down the process for providing aid.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/> [[Doctors Without Borders]] said in late March that supplies of diagnostic equipment and [[personal protective equipment]] were stranded on the Chinese border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early February, the [[North Korean government]] took severe measures to block the spread of the coronavirus. ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'', the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] newspaper, reported that the customs officials at [[Nampho]] port were performing disinfection activities, including placing imported goods in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kcnawatch.org/newstream/1583703072-617647256/\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744-\uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c-\ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4-\uc5c6\uac8c/ |script-title=ko:\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744 \uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c \ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4 \uc5c6\uac8c |language=ko |date=2020-03-09 |accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref> All international flights and railway services were suspended in early February, and connections by sea and road were largely closed over the following weeks.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nIn February, wearing face masks was obligatory and visiting public places such as restaurants was forbidden. Ski resorts and spas were closed and military parades, marathons, and other public events were cancelled.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nSchools were closed throughout the country; university students in Pyongyang from elsewhere in the country were confined to their dormitories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=Sources: N. Korea extends school closures until April 15 |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-north-korea-extends-school-closures-until-april-15/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\">{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=N. Korea closes schools throughout the country for one month |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-closes-schools-throughout-country-one-month/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean citizens returning from other countries were subjected to a 40-day isolation period to which was added a 30-day \"medical observation\" period. According to North Korean media, nearly 7,000 North Koreans were subjected to these rules on 1 March.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nAccording to the North Korean government, 10,000 people had been quarantined by the end of March.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/> From 12 February, the 14-day quarantine on all foreigners (including their local staff) was extended to 30 days.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Diplomats and other foreigners were evacuated to [[Vladivostok]] in March.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/><ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> By 27 March, according to North Korean media, there were only two foreigners in quarantine and 2280 North Koreans were under \"medical observation\" in areas such as [[South Phyongan]] province and [[North Phyongan]] province, [[Ryanggang]] province, and the city of [[Rason]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe North Korean military fired five missiles on two occasions in early March 2020, which may be \"an effort to ensure the country remains on the agenda for other nations amid the virus outbreak\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> More missile tests followed in late March, along with an announcement that the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] would meet in early April. Foreign observers said the government was trying to show confidence in their handling of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Missile tests and meetings: North Korea signals confidence in face of coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea-analysi/missile-tests-and-meetings-north-korea-signals-confidence-in-face-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN21A0O7 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The South Korean military called the provocation \"extremely inappropriate\" in light of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea Fires Missile Into East Sea |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-28/north-korea-fires-missile-into-east-sea-s-korea-military-says |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals.<ref name=\"Fox News\">{{Cite news| url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/kim-jong-un-north-korea-hospital-coronavirus |title = Kim Jong Un orders workers to build new hospitals as North Korea continues to claim no coronavirus cases |work=[[Fox News]] |date = 2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nKim Jong-un sent a letter to South Korean president [[Moon Jae-in]] as a show of support amidst the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|outbreak in South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Top U.S. Commander 'Fairly Certain' North Korea Has Virus Cases |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-14/top-u-s-commander-fairly-certain-north-korea-has-virus-cases |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=14 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] wrote a letter to [[Kim Jong-un]] to express his willingness to work with him on dealing with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea says Trump wrote Kim, offered coronavirus cooperation |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-northkorea-idUSKBN2180YX |work=Reuters |date=2020-03-21}}</ref> North Korean state media has reported on the severity of the outbreak in other countries.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/>\n\nOn 31 March 2020, the ''[[Asia Times]]'' reported that North Korea's measures against the pandemic seemed largely successful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/north-koreas-silent-struggle-against-covid-19/|title=North Korea's silent struggle against Covid-19|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Edwin Salvador, WHO's representative in North Korea, reported that as of 2 April, 709 people had been tested, with no confirmed cases, and 509 people were in quarantine.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea/north-korea-testing-quarantining-for-covid-19-still-says-no-cases-who-representative-idUSKBN21P3C2|title=North Korea testing, quarantining for COVID-19, still says no cases: WHO representative|first=Stephanie|last=Nebehay|publisher=Reuters|date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, Kim Jong-un presided over a meeting of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]. The meeting adopted a joint resolution by the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]], [[State Affairs Commission of North Korea|State Affairs Commission]] and the [[Cabinet of North Korea|Cabinet]], \"On more thoroughly taking national measures for protecting the life and safety of our people from the worldwide epidemic disease\". The resolution called to take strict national countermeasures to thoroughly check the inroads of the virus due to the steady spread of the epidemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/04/kim-jong-un-guides-saturdays-politburo-meeting-ahead-of-spa-state-media/|title=North Korea's Politburo discusses \"danger\" from COVID-19, promotes officials|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, US analyst website [[38 North]] reported that North Korea's early and extensive response appeared to be successful in containing the virus.<ref name=38north-20200423/>\n\n==Impact==\nAlthough South Korean media shared news hinting at the spread of the COVID-19 epidemic to North Korea, the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] denied the veracity of such claims. On 18 February, ''Rodong Sinmun'' quoted a public health official reiterating the country had had \"no confirmed case of the new coronavirus so far\". The WHO prioritised aid for North Korea, including the shipment of protective equipment and supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|title=World Health Organization says there are 'no indications' of coronavirus cases in North Korea|publisher=CNBC|date=19 February 2020|access-date=19 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219100113/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Military===\nIn early March, the North Korean government continued to deny that they had any cases of [[COVID-19]]. However, according to [[South Korea]]n media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'', 180 soldiers had died. There was no estimate of those merely infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3074377/coronavirus-nearly-200-north-korea-soldiers-die-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: nearly 200 North Korea soldiers 'die from outbreak government refuses to acknowledge'|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February and March, U.S. officials observed a decrease in military activity in North Korea, believed to be a sign that there are COVID-19 cases in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> General [[Robert B. Abrams]] observed that the North Korean military had \"been on lockdown for about 30 days\" and \"didn\u2019t fly an airplane for 24 days\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\n===Political===\nThe underground network that assists [[North Korean defectors|defectors in escaping North Korea]] has been almost unable to operate amidst strict controls implemented to stop the virus, with defection attempts being suspended.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\">{{cite news |title=Group of North Korean women and children escape coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.ft.com/content/253d5ff0-63e9-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.ft.com |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Defection rates had been declining already, probably due to increased security under the administrations of [[Kim Jong-un]] in North Korea and [[Xi Jinping]] in China.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\"/>\n\n===Economic===\nOn 26 March, the New York Times reported satellite imagery shared by the [[Royal United Services Institute]], which showed that the illicit trafficking of coal and other goods stopped, with the commercial vessels now idling in their home ports.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/video/coronavirus-north-korea.html</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===January 2020===\nFrom 23 January, North Korea banned [[Tourism in North Korea|foreign tourists]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/north-korea-to-temporarily-ban-tourists-over-wuhan-virus-fears-says-tour-company|title=North Korea to temporarily ban tourists over Wuhan virus fears, says tour company|last=hermesauto|date=21 January 2020|website=The Straits Times|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, suspected cases in [[Sinuiju]] were quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|title=N. Korea quarantines suspected coronavirus cases in Sinuiju|website=Daily NK|date=28 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130223216/https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, North Korea's news agency [[KCNA]] declared a \"state emergency\" and reported the establishment of anti-epidemic headquarters around the country.<ref name=\"20200206cnn\">{{cite news |last1=Berlinger |first1=Joshua |last2=Seo |first2=Yoonjung |title=All of its neighbors have it, so why hasn't North Korea reported any coronavirus cases? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207093221/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html |archive-date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=7 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 2 February, KCNA reported that all the people who had entered the country after 13 January were placed under \"medical supervision\".<ref name=\"20200206cnn\"/>\n\nOn 7 February, South Korean media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'' claimed that five North Koreans in [[Sinuiju]] on the Chinese border died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|title=Sources: Five N. Koreans died from coronavirus infections|author=Jang Seul Gi|website=Daily NK|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082046/https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Within the same day, ''[[The Korea Times]]'' reported that a North Korean female living in the capital [[Pyongyang]] was infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|title=Coronavirus spreads to North Korea, woman infected|website=The Standard|location=Hong Kong|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082206/https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite no confirmation by North Korean authorities on the claims, the country has implemented stricter measures to combat the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pyongyangtimes.com.kp/?bbs=33091|title=Nation steps up fight against novel CoV|website=The Pyongyang Times|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rodong.rep.kp/en/index.php?strPageID=SF01_02_01&newsID=2020-02-08-0001|title=Work to Curb the Inflow of Infectious Disease Pushed ahead with|website=Rodong Sinmun|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed starting on 20 February.<ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\"/>\n\nOn 29 February, [[Kim Jong-un]] called for stronger measures to be taken to prevent COVID-19 from spreading to North Korea.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/kim-warns-consequences-virus-spreads-korea-200229061648473.html | title=Kim warns of 'serious consequences' if virus spreads to N Korea |work=al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 9 March 2020, the South Korean-based [[Daily NK]] reported an informant inside North Korea's military stating that 180 soldiers had died in January and February and about 3,700 soldiers were in quarantine.<ref name=dailynk-20200309>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-almost-200-soldiers-have-died-covid-19/ |title=Sources: Almost 200 soldiers have died from COVID-19 |author=Jeong Tae Joo |newspaper=Daily NK |date=9 March 2020 |access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2020, North Korea state media reported there were no confirmed cases in its territory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Stella |last2=Hagen |first2=Isobel |date=March 14, 2020 |title=North Korea claims it has no coronavirus cases |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/live-blog/coronavirus-updates-live-house-approves-coronavirus-aid-bill-n1158821/ncrd1158881#liveBlogHeader |work=NBC News |access-date=March 14, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals in North Korea. North Korean state media also reported that groundbreaking on a new hospital was underway the day prior on Tuesday 17 March. Kim Jong-un reportedly told a newspaper linked to the ruling [[Workers' Party of Korea]] that the construction of new hospitals were being done for general improvement of the nation's healthcare system without mentioning COVID-19.<ref name=\"Fox News\"/>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, North Korean media stated that more than 2,590 people had been released from quarantine in [[North Pyongan]] and [[South Pyongan]] provinces. All but three quarantined foreigners had been released.<ref name=\"aa.com.tr 21\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: North Korea releases quarantined people |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-north-korea-releases-quarantined-people/1773332 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April 2020, North Korean public health official Pak Myong-su repeated the claim that North Korea has no cases of the virus.<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\">{{cite news |title=N. Korea has no infected people with new coronavirus: expert |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200402/p2g/00m/0in/025000c |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Mainichi Daily News |date=2 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On 23 April 2020, it was reported that the country has taken 740 coronavirus tests, and all of them came back negative.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Norman |first1=Greg |title=North Korea claims 740 coronavirus tests came back negative, thousands released from quarantine |url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/north-korea-claims-740-coronavirus-tests-come-back-negative |website=Fox News |accessdate=24 April 2020 |date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2020, the [[Daily NK]] reported that a defecting North Korean who was shot attempting to cross the Tumen River into China tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korean-tests-positive-for-covid-19-china/|title=N. Korean tests positive for COVID-19 in China|last=Gi|first=Jang Seul|date=2020-04-23|website=Daily NK|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\nIn mid to late April restrictions on foreigners travelling in Pyongyang were relaxed, [[Nampo]] harbour was reopened to container ships, and the 14th [[Supreme People's Assembly]] of hundreds of delegates not wearing face masks was held.<ref name=38north-20200423>{{cite news |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/04/kparkjjongyjung042320/ |title=Do They or Do They Not Have COVID-19 Inside North Korea? |first1=Kee B. |last1=Park |first2=Jessup |last2=Jong |first3=Youngwoo |last3=Jung |publisher=The Henry L. Stimson Center |work=38 North |date=23 April 2020 |access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=38north-20200413>{{cite news |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/04/rfrank041320/ |title=The 2020 Parliamentary Session in North Korea: Self-Criticism and Dubious Optimism Concerning Economic Development |last=Frank |first=Ruediger |publisher=The Henry L. Stimson Center |work=38 North |date=13 April 2020 |access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Health in North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Medicine|North Korea|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 in North Korea|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in North Korea]]\n", "name_user": "Alpha Centauri 5932", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResponse", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_North_Korea"}
{"title_page": "Cinema of Wales", "text_new": "{{Culture of Wales}}\nThe '''Cinema of Wales''' comprises the art of film and creative movies made in [[Wales]] or by [[Welsh people|Welsh]] filmmakers either locally or abroad. Welsh cinema began in the late-19th century, led by Welsh-based director William Haggar. Wales continued to produce film of varying quality throughout the 20th century, in both the [[Welsh language|Welsh]] and [[English language]]s, though indigenous production was curtailed through a lack of infrastructure and finance, which prevented the growth of the industry nationally. Despite this, Wales has been represented in all fields of the film making process, producing actors and directors of note.\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins and early history===\n[[Wales]] has a long film making history, with the first films shot in 1896, just a year after the development of the [[Auguste and Louis Lumi\u00e8re|Lumi\u00e8res']] [[cinematograph]]e. The first known film to be recorded in Wales was by American [[Birt Acres]] featuring a royal visit to [[Cardiff]] by the Prince of Wales, later [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]]. The film was later shown at the Great Fine Art, Industrial and Maritime Exhibition in Cardiff's [[Cathays Park]] in June 1896.<ref name=\"BBC 52 Facts\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/film/pages/52-facts.shtml | title=52 Welsh film facts 1-10| work=BBC Wales | date=5 March 2010 | accessdate=13 February 2011}}</ref> Indigenous film production began in 1898, when [[Rhyl]] based [[Arthur Cheetham]] began recording silent 'short' films of local events. His first film was shown in January 1898 of children playing on Rhyl sands.<ref name=\"BBC 52 Facts\"/>\n[[File:Children playing on Rhyl Sands.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Still from children playing on Rhyl Sands (1898)]]\nThe first Wales based film-maker of enduring stature was [[William Haggar]], who made over 30 fiction films between 1901 and 1908.<ref>Davies (2008) p. 281</ref> Haggar's work received a worldwide audience mainly through the [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont]] and [[Charles Urban Trading Company|Urban]] companies.<ref name=\"Davies282\">Davies (2008) p. 282</ref> Haggar's most notable film was ''[[Desperate Poaching Affray]]'' (1903) which is recognised for its violence, iconoclasm and progressive editing. The film, along with Frank Mottorshaw's ''[[A Daring Daylight Burglary]]'' and Edwin Stanton Porter's ''[[The Great Train Robbery (1903 film)|The Great Train Robbery]]'', has in the early Twenty-first century, been credited with influencing the chase subgenre of American films.<ref>Davies (2008) p. 211</ref>\n\nOther extant pre\u2013Great War films to be shot in Wales were made by film-makers from outside the country. These included the British Biograph Company's film ''Conway Castle'' (1898) and Charles Urban Company's ''Wales, England: Land of Castles and Waterfalls'' (1907).<ref name=\"BBC Culture\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/film/pages/culture.shtml | title=Welsh people and culture in film | work=BBC Wales | date=27 October 2009 | accessdate=13 February 2011}}</ref> The [[1906 British Home Championship]] encounter between Wales and Ireland at Wrexham was filmed by Blackburn firm Mitchell and Keynon, and is now the oldest surviving film of an international football match.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> While the oldest footage of any football match is the 1898 film by Arthur Cheetham, ''Blackburn Rovers v West Bromwich Albion''.<ref name=\"BBC 52 Facts\"/>\n\nDuring the first few decades of Welsh cinema Wales was at the height of an industrial revolution, but there is little sense of the industrial landscape or life captured in the early silent movies taken within the country. Visiting companies, such as [[Edison Studios|Edison]] and [[British and Colonial Films|British and Colonial]] tended to favour filming in rural Wales.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/>\n\n===1914 to 1980===\nMuch of the cinema of Wales in the later 1910s and 1920s has been lost. In 1920 nine films were shot in Wales, all now lost.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> One of the most notable and celebrated of the films from this period is ''A Welsh Singer'' (1915), adapted from a work by Welsh writer [[Allen Raine]], which starred [[Florence Turner]].<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> [[Henry Edwards (actor)|Henry Edwards]] who directed ''A Welsh Singer'', also created the 1930 film ''Aylwin'', from the novel by [[Theodore Watts-Dunton]], drawing into the world of gypsies and a mythical, mystical Wales.<ref name=\"BBC Culture\"/> The 1930s saw the first [[Welsh language]] film, ''[[Y Chwarelwr]]'' directed by [[Ifan ab Owen Edwards]] in 1935. The decade also saw two important [[agitprop]] documentaries, ''[[Today We Live (1937 film)|Today We Live]]'' (1937) set among the unemployed miners of the village of [[Pentre]] in the [[Rhondda|Rhondda Valleys]], and [[Donald Alexander (director)|Donald Alexander]]'s ''[[Eastern Valley]]'' (1937). The outbreak of World War II saw the backdrop of a mining valley in Wales being used as the setting for a war propaganda film, ''[[The Silent Village]]'' (1943). Designed as a tribute to the mining community of [[Lidice]], Czechoslovakia, which had suffered from Nazi atrocities, ''The Silent Village'' transpose the events to a Wales; and was also used to draw analogies with the oppression of the Welsh language.<ref name=\"BBC Culture\"/>\n[[File:Emlyn Williams.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Welsh dramatist and director of ''The Last Days of Dolwyn'', Emlyn Williams]]\nThe coming of the [[Sound film|sound era]] had little impact on Welsh cinema, though 1938's [[The Citadel (1938 film)|The Citadel]] an adaptation of [[A. J. Cronin]]'s [[The Citadel (novel)|1937 novel]] brought Wales to a large audience; though [[King Vidor]]'s interpretation failed to express the novel's political message.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> The first Hollywood 'talkie' to be set in Wales was James Whale's ''[[The Old Dark House (1932 film)|The Old Dark House]]''.<ref name=\"BBC 52 Facts 3\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/film/pages/52-facts-03.shtml | title=52 Welsh film facts | work=BBC Wales | date=5 March 2010 | accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> The best known films connected to Wales during this period failed to harness Welsh talents, ''[[The Proud Valley]]'' (1940) and ''[[How Green Was My Valley (film)|How Green Was My Valley]]'' (1940) were neither directed or adapted for the screen by Welsh people. [[John Ford]]'s How Green Was My Valley is notable for starring just one Welsh actor, [[Rhys Williams (Welsh-American actor)|Rhys Williams]], and for being shot in the United States. Although John Ford's view of Wales was based on a mythical and romantic view of the industrialised valleys, Jill Cragie's [[Blue Scar]] (1949), part financed by the [[National Coal Board]], raised serious and radical questions about the nationalisation of the coal industry and has striking location photography around south Wales.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/><ref name=\"BBC Culture\"/> Another release from 1949 to make an important cultural statement was [[Emlyn Williams]]' ''[[The Last Days of Dolwyn]]'', the plot of which centred on the flooding of a Welsh village to create a reservoir; a subject that became extremely controversial in Wales in the 1960s.<ref name=\"BBC Culture\"/>\n\nThe 1950s and 1960s saw the output of two of the country's best documentary makers. [[Jack Howells (director)|Jack Howells]] and [[John Ormond]] dealt primarily with Welsh people and subjects. Howells is best known for his impressionistic, lyrical documentaries that included ''Nye!'' (1965) and ''[[Dylan Thomas (film)|Dylan Thomas]]'' (1962). ''Dylan Thomas'' is the only Welsh film to have won an Oscar (for [[35th Academy Awards|best short documentary]]), it features Richard Burton as narrator, visiting the haunts of [[Dylan Thomas]].<ref>Davies (2008) p. 380</ref> Ormond, a poet foremost, is remembered for his sensitive portrayals of writers and authors, and for documentaries concerned with the working class and with refugees, in particular ''Borrowed Pasture'' (1960) which follows two Polish ex-soldiers struggling to get by on a [[Carmarthenshire]] smallholding.<ref>Davies (2008) p. 633</ref>\n\nThe period directly following the end of the Second World War saw political and social commentary disappear from Welsh cinema. The first few decades after the war saw few notable Welsh films; stand out exceptions included ''[[Tiger Bay (1959 film)|Tiger Bay]]'' (1959) and ''[[Only Two Can Play]]'' (1962).<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> The main problems facing Welsh cinema during this period were a lack of a film production infrastructure, Welsh producers and finance. The fact that Wales was unable to produce films from within its own borders resulted in the stereotyping and common preconceptions of Welsh life formed by 'outside' film-makers.<ref name=\"Davies283\">Davies (2008) p. 283</ref> One of the few beacons of light for the industry came in the late 1970s with the output of left wing producer and director [[Karl Francis]]; whose controversial portrayal of contemporary life in the south Wales valleys was typified by his 1976 film ''[[Above us the Earth]]''.<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> Welsh language films were few, notably the films produced in the 1970s by the Bwrdd Ffilmiau Cymraeg (Welsh Film Board).\n\nBefore the advent of a dedicated channel, [[BBC Wales]] and its commercial counterpart [[ITV Wales & West|HTV]] produced Welsh language programmes for their viewers in Wales. Although this did not include the creation of feature-length films, in the 1970s HTV undertook a venture to [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dub]] existing movies into Welsh. Their first attempt was George Stevens' 1953 Western, ''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]''. The result was seen as a unintentionally humorous and the experiment was quickly abandoned.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/westminster_hall/2001/apr/24/digital-television | title=House of Commons debate: Digital Television | publisher=millbanksystems.com | author=[[Simon Thomas (politician)|Thomas, Simon]] | date=24 April 2001 | accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaea.org/index.php?k=12068 |title=The role of Adult education in preserving the identity of an ethnic minority: the Welsh case |publisher=eaea.org |work=European Association for the Education of Adults |author=Evans, J.R.P. |year=1991 |accessdate=11 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405224103/http://www.eaea.org/index.php?k=12068 |archivedate=5 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Could+George+Bush+follow+Shane+as+the+new+'Cymru+cowboyo'%3F-a0170459678 | title=Could George Bush follow Shane as the new 'Cymru cowboyo'? | publisher=thefreelibrary.com |work=Western Mail | author=Clark, Rhodri | date=31 October 2007 | accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n_vUx1TtH5AC&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218&dq=dubbed+welsh+shane#v=onepage&q=dubbed%20welsh%20shane&f=false | title=Modern Wales: A Concise History | publisher=Cambridge University Press | author=Jones, Gareth Elwyn | date=1994 |page=218 | accessdate=11 July 2012| isbn=9780521469456 }}</ref>\n\n===1980 to present===\n1982 saw the launch of [[S4C]], a Welsh language television channel, which began producing and funding longer dramas and films in the Welsh and English language. Initial output was poor, but after reassessing its responsibilities in 1986, the company produced films of note, including ''Boy Soldier'' (1986) and ''[[Rhosyn a Rhith]]'' (1986), the latter being the first film in the Welsh language to gain a London West End cinema release.<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> Although the production of Welsh features from S4C was low, it aided the emergence of talented Welsh film-makers, such as [[Endaf Emlyn]], [[Marc Evans]] and [[Stephen Bayly]].<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> S4C's 1995 policy, to produce up to two feature films a year, to be released to cinemas before television transmission allowed Welsh film-makers new opportunities. Yet the reluctance of London-based distributors to handle Welsh language films make it difficult for Welsh films to reach a wider audience.<ref name=\"Davies283\"/>\n\nThe early 1990s began with the release of Welsh language film ''[[Hedd Wyn (film)|Hedd Wyn]]''. It won the [[Royal Television Society]] Best Drama award and became the first Welsh film to gain a nomination in the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]. Despite this it failed to gain a British distributor.<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> The 1990s also saw two important films from Endaf Emlyn, ''[[Un Nos Ola Leuad]]'' (1991) is seen as one of the finest Welsh films made,<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> while his ''Gadael Lenin'' (1993) was voted by viewers at the 1993 London Film Festival as the most popular British film.\n\nThe later 1990s saw three English language films that found a home in mainstream British cinema. The first of the three was Marc Evans' ''[[House of America]]'' which drew comparisons to the realism of Karl Francis' work. Then in 1998, [[Kevin Allen (actor)|Kevin Allen]] produced [[Twin Town]], a bawdy comedy satirising the older cultural traditions of Wales. This though was surpassed at the box office by [[Justin Kerrigan]]'s ''[[Human Traffic]]'' (1999), a stylised comedy focusing on the club and drug culture of Cardiff. 2000 saw the release of [[Paul Morrison (director)|Paul Morrison's]] ''[[Solomon & Gaenor]]'' the second film to be nominated for the foreign language Academy Award.\n\nFilms of note in the early twenty-first century set in Wales include comedies ''[[House!]]'' (2000) and ''[[Very Annie Mary]]'' (2000), and horror films ''[[The Dark (film)|The Dark]]'' (2005) and ''[[Evil Aliens]]'' (2006). In 2009 a biopic of the early relationship between Welsh poet [[Dylan Thomas]] and his wife [[Caitlin Thomas|Caitlin Macnamara]] was released entitled ''[[The Edge of Love]]''.\n\nDespite an improvement in film production in Wales, finance is still an issue with very few films being created without external funding. ''House of America'' took its funding from six different sources while Multinationals funded both ''Twin Town'' ([[PolyGram]]) and ''[[The Englishman Who Went Up a Hill But Came Down a Mountain]]'' ([[Miramax Films|Miramax]]).\n\nFilm in Wales is supported by [[BAFTA Cymru]] (established 1991), the Welsh branch of the [[BAFTA|British Academy of Film and Television Arts]]. Bafta Cymru holds an annual awards ceremony to recognise achievements is Welsh cinema, but unlike its parent body, the television and film awards are contested together for each category.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bafta.org/wales/about/ | title=About Bafta in Wales| work=BAFTA Cymru | date= | accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Animation==\nPrior to the formation of S4C in 1982, there was very little work produced in the field of [[animation]] in Wales. The one notable exception being Sid Griffiths' ''[[Jerry the Tyke]]'' (1925-1927), a mischievous dog who was used for Path\u00e9 cinema news magazines.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2002/09_september/19/rhys_ifans.shtml | title=Rhys Ifans rejuvenates Jerry the Tyke | work=BBC | date=9 September 2002 | accessdate=16 February 2011}}</ref> Production increased after 1982, with S4C producing the popular children's animation [[SuperTed]] made by [[Siriol Productions]]. Siriol eventually branched into making feature length animations, including an adaptation of Dylan Thomas' [[Under Milk Wood]] (1992) and a joint venture with Hungarian company [[Pann\u00f3niaFilm]], [[The Princess and the Goblin (film)|The Princess and the Goblin]] (1992).\n\nThe opportunities afforded by S4C's animation unit encouraged an influx of talented British artists into Wales.<ref>Davies (2008) p. 284</ref> The best known of this group of animators was [[Joanna Quinn]], who gained an [[70th Academy Awards|Oscar nomination in 1998]] for ''[[Famous Fred]]'', and produced one of the segments of ''The Canterbury Tales'', which was [[71st Academy Awards|Oscar nominated the year after]].\n\n==Welsh film directors==\nWales has produced film directors of quality throughout its history, though those that have found success have more often needed to leave Wales to gain recognition. Although based in Wales neither Cheetham or Haggar were Welsh born, similar for [[Sidney Northcote]] who in 1912 produced a number of short films shot on location in Wales and Cornwall, based on Welsh and Cornish myths and tales, including ''The Pedlar of Penmaenmawr'', ''The Witch of the Welsh Mountains'' and ''The Belle of Bettwys-y-Coed''.<ref>Berry (1996) p. 453</ref>\n\nWelsh-born directors who have gained international recognition include [[Richard Marquand]], (''[[Return of the Jedi]]''), [[Peter Greenaway]] (''[[Drowning by Numbers]]'') and [[Terry Jones]] (''[[Erik the Viking]]''). Two of the more notable directors from Wales who have retained a strong connection with the culture of Wales are Karl Francis, who for two decades was the most powerful, distinctive and combative voice in Welsh film-making;<ref>Berry (1996) p. 376</ref> and [[Stephen Weeks]] whose commercial features look back to a medieval or imperialist past, or a misty Celtic world.<ref>Berry (1996) p. 400</ref> Francis' work is embedded in a realistic exploration of Wales, its language and identity, in films such as ''Milwr Bychan'' (Boy Soldier) and ''The Mouse and the Women''. Weeks came to prominence after directing [[I, Monster]], an adaptation of ''Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde'' starring Christopher Lee and Peter Cushing. Weeks would later film two versions of the [[Arthurian]] myth of ''[[Gawain and the Green Knight]]''. First as ''[[Gawain and the Green Knight (1973 film)|Gawain and the Green Knight]]'' (1973) featuring [[Murray Head]] in the lead role and again as ''[[Sword of the Valiant]]'' in 1984.<ref>Berry (1996) pp. 404-407</ref>\n\nLater Welsh directors, such as [[Sara Sugarman]] and Marc Evans made films set in Wales.\n\n==Welsh movie actors==\nWales has a long tradition of producing film-actors who have made an impact on the world stage. During the silent period Welsh actors of note included [[Ivor Novello]], who came to prominence through cinema after starring in ''[[The Lodger: A Story of the London Fog|The Lodger]]'' (1927) and ''[[Downhill (1927 film)|Downhill]]'' (1927); [[Gareth Hughes]], often cast as a youthful charmer, gained excellent notices for the now-lost ''[[Sentimental Tommy]]'' (1921) and [[Lyn Harding]], whose stature and presence made him a sought after villain playing [[Professor Moriarty|Moriarty]] in several early [[Sherlock Holmes films]].\n[[File:AnthonyHopkins10TIFF.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Welsh actor, [[Anthony Hopkins]]]]\nThe 1940s saw [[Rhondda]]'s [[Donald Houston]] breakthrough in his first two features ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1949 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'' (1949) and ''[[A Run for Your Money]]'' (1949). In 1945 [[Ray Milland]] became the first Welsh actor to win the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]], for his role as an alcoholic writer in ''[[The Lost Weekend (film)|The Lost Weekend]]''.\n\nThe most significant period for Welsh actors came during the 1950s and 1960s. A new wave of realism entered British acting, and at the forefront came Welsh actors [[Richard Burton]], [[Stanley Baker]] and [[Rachel Roberts (actress)|Rachel Roberts]]. The period also saw Welsh character actors such as [[Hugh Griffith]], who won the Best Supporting Actor Academy Award for his role in the 1959 version of ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben Hur]]''.\n\nAnother famous Welsh actor is [[Timothy Dalton]] who portrayed famous secret agent [[James Bond]] twice at the end of the eighties. \n\nThe most distinctive Welsh actor of the 1990s through to the 2000s was [[Anthony Hopkins]]. Hopkins has appeared in film since the 1960s, starring in Hollywood costume dramas such as ''[[The Lion in Winter (1968 film)|The Lion in Winter]]''. Starring in films as diverse as [[Richard Attenborough]]'s ''[[Magic (1978 film)|Magic]]'' and [[David Lynch]]'s ''[[The Elephant Man (film)|The Elephant Man]]'', Hopkins became a Hollywood star after his Academy Award winning performance as [[Hannibal Lecter]] in ''[[The Silence of the Lambs (film)|The Silence of the Lambs]]'' (1992). Hopkins continued to impress throughout the 1990s with critically acclaimed performances in ''[[Shadowlands (1993 film)|Shadowlands]]'' and ''[[Remains of the Day]]''.\n\nThe 1990s produced an abrasive group of Welsh actors, including [[Rhys Ifans]] and [[Matthew Rhys]]. The 1990s also saw the success of [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]], who became one of Hollywood's highest paid stars, appearing alongside [[Antonio Banderas]] and Anthony Hopkins in ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]'' and won the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for ''[[Chicago (2002 film)|Chicago]]''. The 2000s are most notable for the emergence of [[Ioan Gruffudd]], who took the lead role in the 2006 historical drama ''[[Amazing Grace (2006 film)|Amazing Grace]]'', and [[Michael Sheen]] who appeared as [[Tony Blair]] in [[Peter Morgan]]'s ''Blair Trilogy'' and played [[David Frost]] in ''[[Frost/Nixon (film)|Frost/Nixon]]''. One of the biggest movie stars to come out of Wales is [[Academy Award|Oscar]] winning [[actor]] [[Christian Bale]]. He is well known for portraying [[Batman]]/[[Bruce Wayne]] in critically and commercially acclaimed The Dark Knight Trilogy. He has been nominated three times for [[The Fighter]], [[American Hustle]] and [[The Big Short (film)|The Big Short]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Welsh films]]\n* [[List of cinema of the world]]\n** [[Cinema of Europe]]\n*** [[Cinema of the United Kingdom]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Davies|editor1-link=John Davies (historian)|editor2-first=Nigel |editor2-last=Jenkins | editor2-link=Nigel Jenkins| editor3-first=Baines |editor3-last=Menna|editor4-first=Peredur I. |editor4-last=Lynch|title=The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |year=2008 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff |isbn=978-0-7083-1953-6}}\n* {{cite book |last=Berry|first=David|title=Wales and Cinema, The First Hundred Years |year=1996 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff |page= |isbn=0-7083-1370-1}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061205232125/http://screenandsound.llgc.org.uk/001.htm The National Screen and Sound Archive of Wales]\n*https://player.bfi.org.uk/britain-on-film \n\n{{Worldcinema}}\n\n[[Category:Cinema of Wales| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Culture of Wales}}\nThe '''Cinema of Wales''' comprises the art of film and creative movies made in [[Wales]] or by [[Welsh people|Welsh]] filmmakers either locally or abroad. Welsh cinema began in the late-19th century, led by Welsh-based director William Haggar. Wales continued to produce film of varying quality throughout the 20th century, in both the [[Welsh language|Welsh]] and [[English language]]s, though indigenous production was curtailed through a lack of infrastructure and finance, which prevented the growth of the industry nationally. Despite this, Wales has been represented in all fields of the film making process, producing actors and directors of note.\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins and early history===\n[[Wales]] has a long film making history, with the first films shot in 1896, just a year after the development of the [[Auguste and Louis Lumi\u00e8re|Lumi\u00e8res']] [[cinematograph]]e. The first known film to be recorded in Wales was by American [[Birt Acres]] featuring a royal visit to [[Cardiff]] by the Prince of Wales, later [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]]. The film was later shown at the Great Fine Art, Industrial and Maritime Exhibition in Cardiff's [[Cathays Park]] in June 1896.<ref name=\"BBC 52 Facts\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/film/pages/52-facts.shtml | title=52 Welsh film facts 1-10| work=BBC Wales | date=5 March 2010 | accessdate=13 February 2011}}</ref> Indigenous film production began in 1898, when [[Rhyl]] based [[Arthur Cheetham]] began recording silent 'short' films of local events. His first film was shown in January 1898 of children playing on Rhyl sands.<ref name=\"BBC 52 Facts\"/>\n[[File:Children playing on Rhyl Sands.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Still from children playing on Rhyl Sands (1898)]]\nThe first Wales based film-maker of enduring stature was [[William Haggar]], who made over 30 fiction films between 1901 and 1908.<ref>Davies (2008) p. 281</ref> Haggar's work received a worldwide audience mainly through the [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont]] and [[Charles Urban Trading Company|Urban]] companies.<ref name=\"Davies282\">Davies (2008) p. 282</ref> Haggar's most notable film was ''[[Desperate Poaching Affray]]'' (1903) which is recognised for its violence, iconoclasm and progressive editing. The film, along with Frank Mottorshaw's ''[[A Daring Daylight Burglary]]'' and Edwin Stanton Porter's ''[[The Great Train Robbery (1903 film)|The Great Train Robbery]]'', has in the early Twenty-first century, been credited with influencing the chase subgenre of American films.<ref>Davies (2008) p. 211</ref>\n\nOther extant pre\u2013Great War films to be shot in Wales were made by film-makers from outside the country. These included the British Biograph Company's film ''Conway Castle'' (1898) and Charles Urban Company's ''Wales, England: Land of Castles and Waterfalls'' (1907).<ref name=\"BBC Culture\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/film/pages/culture.shtml | title=Welsh people and culture in film | work=BBC Wales | date=27 October 2009 | accessdate=13 February 2011}}</ref> The [[1906 British Home Championship]] encounter between Wales and Ireland at Wrexham was filmed by Blackburn firm Mitchell and Keynon, and is now the oldest surviving film of an international football match.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> While the oldest footage of any football match is the 1898 film by Arthur Cheetham, ''Blackburn Rovers v West Bromwich Albion''.<ref name=\"BBC 52 Facts\"/>\n\nDuring the first few decades of Welsh cinema Wales was at the height of an industrial revolution, but there is little sense of the industrial landscape or life captured in the early silent movies taken within the country. Visiting companies, such as [[Edison Studios|Edison]] and [[British and Colonial Films|British and Colonial]] tended to favour filming in rural Wales.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/>\n\n===1914 to 1980===\nMuch of the cinema of Wales in the later 1910s and 1920s has been lost. In 1920 nine films were shot in Wales, all now lost.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> One of the most notable and celebrated of the films from this period is ''A Welsh Singer'' (1915), adapted from a work by Welsh writer [[Allen Raine]], which starred [[Florence Turner]].<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> [[Henry Edwards (actor)|Henry Edwards]] who directed ''A Welsh Singer'', also created the 1930 film ''Aylwin'', from the novel by [[Theodore Watts-Dunton]], drawing into the world of gypsies and a mythical, mystical Wales.<ref name=\"BBC Culture\"/> The 1930s saw the first [[Welsh language]] film, ''[[Y Chwarelwr]]'' directed by [[Ifan ab Owen Edwards]] in 1935. The decade also saw two important [[agitprop]] documentaries, ''[[Today We Live (1937 film)|Today We Live]]'' (1937) set among the unemployed miners of the village of [[Pentre]] in the [[Rhondda|Rhondda Valleys]], and [[Donald Alexander (director)|Donald Alexander]]'s ''[[Eastern Valley]]'' (1937). The outbreak of World War II saw the backdrop of a mining valley in Wales being used as the setting for a war propaganda film, ''[[The Silent Village]]'' (1943). Designed as a tribute to the mining community of [[Lidice]], Czechoslovakia, which had suffered from Nazi atrocities, ''The Silent Village'' transpose the events to a Wales; and was also used to draw analogies with the oppression of the Welsh language.<ref name=\"BBC Culture\"/>\n[[File:Emlyn Williams.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Welsh dramatist and director of ''The Last Days of Dolwyn'', Emlyn Williams]]\nThe coming of the [[Sound film|sound era]] had little impact on Welsh cinema, though 1938's [[The Citadel (1938 film)|The Citadel]] an adaptation of [[A. J. Cronin]]'s [[The Citadel (novel)|1937 novel]] brought Wales to a large audience; though [[King Vidor]]'s interpretation failed to express the novel's political message.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> The first Hollywood 'talkie' to be set in Wales was James Whale's ''[[The Old Dark House (1932 film)|The Old Dark House]]''.<ref name=\"BBC 52 Facts 3\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/film/pages/52-facts-03.shtml | title=52 Welsh film facts | work=BBC Wales | date=5 March 2010 | accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> The best known films connected to Wales during this period failed to harness Welsh talents, ''[[The Proud Valley]]'' (1940) and ''[[How Green Was My Valley (film)|How Green Was My Valley]]'' (1940) were neither directed or adapted for the screen by Welsh people. [[John Ford]]'s How Green Was My Valley is notable for starring just one Welsh actor, [[Rhys Williams (Welsh-American actor)|Rhys Williams]], and for being shot in the United States. Although John Ford's view of Wales was based on a mythical and romantic view of the industrialised valleys, Jill Cragie's [[Blue Scar]] (1949), part financed by the [[National Coal Board]], raised serious and radical questions about the nationalisation of the coal industry and has striking location photography around south Wales.<ref name=\"Davies282\"/><ref name=\"BBC Culture\"/> Another release from 1949 to make an important cultural statement was [[Emlyn Williams]]' ''[[The Last Days of Dolwyn]]'', the plot of which centred on the flooding of a Welsh village to create a reservoir; a subject that became extremely controversial in Wales in the 1960s.<ref name=\"BBC Culture\"/>\n\nThe 1950s and 1960s saw the output of two of the country's best documentary makers. [[Jack Howells (director)|Jack Howells]] and [[John Ormond]] dealt primarily with Welsh people and subjects. Howells is best known for his impressionistic, lyrical documentaries that included ''Nye!'' (1965) and ''[[Dylan Thomas (film)|Dylan Thomas]]'' (1962). ''Dylan Thomas'' is the only Welsh film to have won an Oscar (for [[35th Academy Awards|best short documentary]]), it features Richard Burton as narrator, visiting the haunts of [[Dylan Thomas]].<ref>Davies (2008) p. 380</ref> Ormond, a poet foremost, is remembered for his sensitive portrayals of writers and authors, and for documentaries concerned with the working class and with refugees, in particular ''Borrowed Pasture'' (1960) which follows two Polish ex-soldiers struggling to get by on a [[Carmarthenshire]] smallholding.<ref>Davies (2008) p. 633</ref>\n\nThe period directly following the end of the Second World War saw political and social commentary disappear from Welsh cinema. The first few decades after the war saw few notable Welsh films; stand out exceptions included ''[[Tiger Bay (1959 film)|Tiger Bay]]'' (1959) and ''[[Only Two Can Play]]'' (1962).<ref name=\"Davies282\"/> The main problems facing Welsh cinema during this period were a lack of a film production infrastructure, Welsh producers and finance. The fact that Wales was unable to produce films from within its own borders resulted in the stereotyping and common preconceptions of Welsh life formed by 'outside' film-makers.<ref name=\"Davies283\">Davies (2008) p. 283</ref> One of the few beacons of light for the industry came in the late 1970s with the output of left wing producer and director [[Karl Francis]]; whose controversial portrayal of contemporary life in the south Wales valleys was typified by his 1976 film ''[[Above us the Earth]]''.<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> Welsh language films were few, notably the films produced in the 1970s by the Bwrdd Ffilmiau Cymraeg (Welsh Film Board).\n\nBefore the advent of a dedicated channel, [[BBC Wales]] and its commercial counterpart [[ITV Wales & West|HTV]] produced Welsh language programmes for their viewers in Wales. Although this did not include the creation of feature-length films, in the 1970s HTV undertook a venture to [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dub]] existing movies into Welsh. Their first attempt was George Stevens' 1953 Western, ''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]''. The result was seen as a unintentionally humorous and the experiment was quickly abandoned.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/westminster_hall/2001/apr/24/digital-television | title=House of Commons debate: Digital Television | publisher=millbanksystems.com | author=[[Simon Thomas (politician)|Thomas, Simon]] | date=24 April 2001 | accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaea.org/index.php?k=12068 |title=The role of Adult education in preserving the identity of an ethnic minority: the Welsh case |publisher=eaea.org |work=European Association for the Education of Adults |author=Evans, J.R.P. |year=1991 |accessdate=11 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405224103/http://www.eaea.org/index.php?k=12068 |archivedate=5 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Could+George+Bush+follow+Shane+as+the+new+'Cymru+cowboyo'%3F-a0170459678 | title=Could George Bush follow Shane as the new 'Cymru cowboyo'? | publisher=thefreelibrary.com |work=Western Mail | author=Clark, Rhodri | date=31 October 2007 | accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n_vUx1TtH5AC&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218&dq=dubbed+welsh+shane#v=onepage&q=dubbed%20welsh%20shane&f=false | title=Modern Wales: A Concise History | publisher=Cambridge University Press | author=Jones, Gareth Elwyn | date=1994 |page=218 | accessdate=11 July 2012| isbn=9780521469456 }}</ref>\n\n===1980 to present===\n1982 saw the launch of [[S4C]], a Welsh language television channel, which began producing and funding longer dramas and films in the Welsh and English language. Initial output was poor, but after reassessing its responsibilities in 1986, the company produced films of note, including ''Boy Soldier'' (1986) and ''[[Rhosyn a Rhith]]'' (1986), the latter being the first film in the Welsh language to gain a London West End cinema release.<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> Although the production of Welsh features from S4C was low, it aided the emergence of talented Welsh film-makers, such as [[Endaf Emlyn]], [[Marc Evans]] and [[Stephen Bayly]].<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> S4C's 1995 policy, to produce up to two feature films a year, to be released to cinemas before television transmission allowed Welsh film-makers new opportunities. Yet the reluctance of London-based distributors to handle Welsh language films make it difficult for Welsh films to reach a wider audience.<ref name=\"Davies283\"/>\n\nThe early 1990s began with the release of Welsh language film ''[[Hedd Wyn (film)|Hedd Wyn]]''. It won the [[Royal Television Society]] Best Drama award and became the first Welsh film to gain a nomination in the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]. Despite this it failed to gain a British distributor.<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> The 1990s also saw two important films from Endaf Emlyn, ''[[Un Nos Ola Leuad]]'' (1991) is seen as one of the finest Welsh films made,<ref name=\"Davies283\"/> while his ''Gadael Lenin'' (1993) was voted by viewers at the 1993 London Film Festival as the most popular British film.\n\nThe later 1990s saw three English language films that found a home in mainstream British cinema. The first of the three was Marc Evans' ''[[House of America]]'' which drew comparisons to the realism of Karl Francis' work. Then in 1998, [[Kevin Allen (actor)|Kevin Allen]] produced [[Twin Town]], a bawdy comedy satirising the older cultural traditions of Wales. This though was surpassed at the box office by [[Justin Kerrigan]]'s ''[[Human Traffic]]'' (1999), a stylised comedy focusing on the club and drug culture of Cardiff. 2000 saw the release of [[Paul Morrison (director)|Paul Morrison's]] ''[[Solomon & Gaenor]]'' the second film to be nominated for the foreign language Academy Award.\n\nFilms of note in the early twenty-first century set in Wales include comedies ''[[House!]]'' (2000) and ''[[Very Annie Mary]]'' (2000), and horror films ''[[The Dark (film)|The Dark]]'' (2005) and ''[[Evil Aliens]]'' (2006). In 2009 a biopic of the early relationship between Welsh poet [[Dylan Thomas]] and his wife [[Caitlin Thomas|Caitlin Macnamara]] was released entitled ''[[The Edge of Love]]''.\n\nDespite an improvement in film production in Wales, finance is still an issue with very few films being created without external funding. ''House of America'' took its funding from six different sources while Multinationals funded both ''Twin Town'' ([[PolyGram]]) and ''[[The Englishman Who Went Up a Hill But Came Down a Mountain]]'' ([[Miramax Films|Miramax]]).\n\nFilm in Wales is supported by [[BAFTA Cymru]] (established 1991), the Welsh branch of the [[BAFTA|British Academy of Film and Television Arts]]. Bafta Cymru holds an annual awards ceremony to recognise achievements is Welsh cinema, but unlike its parent body, the television and film awards are contested together for each category.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bafta.org/wales/about/ | title=About Bafta in Wales| work=BAFTA Cymru | date= | accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Animation==\nPrior to the formation of S4C in 1982, there was very little work produced in the field of [[animation]] in Wales. The one notable exception being Sid Griffiths' ''[[Jerry the Tyke]]'' (1925-1927), a mischievous dog who was used for Path\u00e9 cinema news magazines.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2002/09_september/19/rhys_ifans.shtml | title=Rhys Ifans rejuvenates Jerry the Tyke | work=BBC | date=9 September 2002 | accessdate=16 February 2011}}</ref> Production increased after 1982, with S4C producing the popular children's animation [[SuperTed]] made by [[Siriol Productions]]. Siriol eventually branched into making feature length animations, including an adaptation of Dylan Thomas' [[Under Milk Wood]] (1992) and a joint venture with Hungarian company [[Pann\u00f3niaFilm]], [[The Princess and the Goblin (film)|The Princess and the Goblin]] (1992).\n\nThe opportunities afforded by S4C's animation unit encouraged an influx of talented British artists into Wales.<ref>Davies (2008) p. 284</ref> The best known of this group of animators was [[Joanna Quinn]], who gained an [[70th Academy Awards|Oscar nomination in 1998]] for ''[[Famous Fred]]'', and produced one of the segments of ''The Canterbury Tales'', which was [[71st Academy Awards|Oscar nominated the year after]].\n\n==Welsh film directors==\nWales has produced film directors of quality throughout its history, though those that have found success have more often needed to leave Wales to gain recognition. Although based in Wales neither Cheetham or Haggar were Welsh born, similar for [[Sidney Northcote]] who in 1912 produced a number of short films shot on location in Wales and Cornwall, based on Welsh and Cornish myths and tales, including ''The Pedlar of Penmaenmawr'', ''The Witch of the Welsh Mountains'' and ''The Belle of Bettwys-y-Coed''.<ref>Berry (1996) p. 453</ref>\n\nWelsh-born directors who have gained international recognition include [[Richard Marquand]], (''[[Return of the Jedi]]''), [[Peter Greenaway]] (''[[Drowning by Numbers]]'') and [[Terry Jones]] (''[[Erik the Viking]]''). Two of the more notable directors from Wales who have retained a strong connection with the culture of Wales are Karl Francis, who for two decades was the most powerful, distinctive and combative voice in Welsh film-making;<ref>Berry (1996) p. 376</ref> and [[Stephen Weeks]] whose commercial features look back to a medieval or imperialist past, or a misty Celtic world.<ref>Berry (1996) p. 400</ref> Francis' work is embedded in a realistic exploration of Wales, its language and identity, in films such as ''Milwr Bychan'' (Boy Soldier) and ''The Mouse and the Women''. Weeks came to prominence after directing [[I, Monster]], an adaptation of ''Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde'' starring Christopher Lee and Peter Cushing. Weeks would later film two versions of the [[Arthurian]] myth of ''[[Gawain and the Green Knight]]''. First as ''[[Gawain and the Green Knight (1973 film)|Gawain and the Green Knight]]'' (1973) featuring [[Murray Head]] in the lead role and again as ''[[Sword of the Valiant]]'' in 1984.<ref>Berry (1996) pp. 404-407</ref>\n\nLater Welsh directors, such as [[Sara Sugarman]] and Marc Evans made films set in Wales.\n\n==Welsh movie actors==\nWales has a long tradition of producing film-actors who have made an impact on the world stage. During the silent period Welsh actors of note included [[Ivor Novello]], who came to prominence through cinema after starring in ''[[The Lodger: A Story of the London Fog|The Lodger]]'' (1927) and ''[[Downhill (1927 film)|Downhill]]'' (1927); [[Gareth Hughes]], often cast as a youthful charmer, gained excellent notices for the now-lost ''[[Sentimental Tommy]]'' (1921) and [[Lyn Harding]], whose stature and presence made him a sought after villain playing [[Professor Moriarty|Moriarty]] in several early [[Sherlock Holmes films]].\n[[File:AnthonyHopkins10TIFF.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Welsh actor, [[Anthony Hopkins]]]]\nThe 1940s saw [[Rhondda]]'s [[Donald Houston]] breakthrough in his first two features ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1949 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'' (1949) and ''[[A Run for Your Money]]'' (1949). In 1945 [[Ray Milland]] became the first Welsh actor to win the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]], for his role as an alcoholic writer in ''[[The Lost Weekend (film)|The Lost Weekend]]''.\n\nThe most significant period for Welsh actors came during the 1950s and 1960s. A new wave of realism entered British acting, and at the forefront came Welsh actors [[Richard Burton]], [[Stanley Baker]] and [[Rachel Roberts (actress)|Rachel Roberts]]. The period also saw Welsh character actors such as [[Hugh Griffith]], who won the Best Supporting Actor Academy Award for his role in the 1959 version of ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben Hur]]''.\n\nOne of the biggest movie stars to come out of Wales is [[Academy Award|Oscar]] winning [[actor]] [[Christian Bale]]. He is well known for portraying [[Batman]]/[[Bruce Wayne]] in critically and commercially acclaimed The Dark Knight Trilogy.\nHe has been nominated three times for [[The Fighter]], [[American Hustle]] and [[The Big Short (film)|The Big Short]]. \n\nThe most distinctive Welsh actor of the 1990s through to the 2000s was [[Anthony Hopkins]]. Hopkins has appeared in film since the 1960s, starring in Hollywood costume dramas such as ''[[The Lion in Winter (1968 film)|The Lion in Winter]]''. Starring in films as diverse as [[Richard Attenborough]]'s ''[[Magic (1978 film)|Magic]]'' and [[David Lynch]]'s ''[[The Elephant Man (film)|The Elephant Man]]'', Hopkins became a Hollywood star after his Academy Award winning performance as [[Hannibal Lecter]] in ''[[The Silence of the Lambs (film)|The Silence of the Lambs]]'' (1992). Hopkins continued to impress throughout the 1990s with critically acclaimed performances in ''[[Shadowlands (1993 film)|Shadowlands]]'' and ''[[Remains of the Day]]''.\n\nAnother famous Welsh actor is [[Timothy Dalton]] who portrayed famous secret agent [[James Bond]] twice at the end of the eighties.\n\nThe 1990s produced an abrasive group of Welsh actors, including [[Rhys Ifans]] and [[Matthew Rhys]]. The 1990s also saw the success of [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]], who became one of Hollywood's highest paid stars, appearing alongside [[Antonio Banderas]] and Anthony Hopkins in ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]'' and won the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for ''[[Chicago (2002 film)|Chicago]]''. The 2000s are most notable for the emergence of [[Ioan Gruffudd]], who took the lead role in the 2006 historical drama ''[[Amazing Grace (2006 film)|Amazing Grace]]'', and [[Michael Sheen]] who appeared as [[Tony Blair]] in [[Peter Morgan]]'s ''Blair Trilogy'' and played [[David Frost]] in ''[[Frost/Nixon (film)|Frost/Nixon]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Welsh films]]\n* [[List of cinema of the world]]\n** [[Cinema of Europe]]\n*** [[Cinema of the United Kingdom]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Davies|editor1-link=John Davies (historian)|editor2-first=Nigel |editor2-last=Jenkins | editor2-link=Nigel Jenkins| editor3-first=Baines |editor3-last=Menna|editor4-first=Peredur I. |editor4-last=Lynch|title=The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |year=2008 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff |isbn=978-0-7083-1953-6}}\n* {{cite book |last=Berry|first=David|title=Wales and Cinema, The First Hundred Years |year=1996 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff |page= |isbn=0-7083-1370-1}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061205232125/http://screenandsound.llgc.org.uk/001.htm The National Screen and Sound Archive of Wales]\n*https://player.bfi.org.uk/britain-on-film \n\n{{Worldcinema}}\n\n[[Category:Cinema of Wales| ]]\n", "name_user": "Dnaoro", "label": "safe", "comment": "chronological shuffle of sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cinema_of_Wales"}
